items.description: The Continent Pokémon. Small Pokémon occasionally gather on its unmoving back to begin building their nests.

items.name: Chimchar
items.description: The Chimp Pokémon. It agilely scales sheer cliffs to live atop craggy mountains. Its fire is put out when it sleeps.

items.name: Monferno
items.description: The Playful Pokémon. To intimidate attackers, it stretches the fire on its tail to make itself appear bigger.

items.name: Infernape
items.description: The Flame Pokémon. It uses a special kind of martial arts involving all its limbs. Its fire never goes out.

items.name: Piplup
items.description: The Penguin Pokémon. Because it is very proud, it hates accepting food from people. Its thick down guards it from cold.

items.name: Prinplup
items.description: The Penguin Pokémon. It lives alone, away from others. Apparently, every one of them believes it is the most important.

items.name: Empoleon
items.description: The Emperor Pokémon. The three horns that extend from its beak attest to its power. The leader has the biggest horns.

items.name: Starly
items.description: The Starling Pokémon. They flock in great numbers. Though small, they flap their wings with great power.

items.name: Staravia
items.description: The Starling Pokémon. It flies around forests and fields in search of bug Pokémon. It stays within a huge flock.

items.name: Staraptor
items.description: The Predator Pokémon. It has a savage nature. It will courageously challenge foes that are much larger.

items.name: Bidoof
items.description: The Plump Mouse Pokémon. With nerves of steel, nothing can perturb it. It is more agile and active than it appears.

items.name: Bibarel
items.description: The Beaver Pokémon. It makes its nest by damming streams with bark and mud. It is known as an industrious worker.

items.name: Kricketot
items.description: The Cricket Pokémon. It shakes its head back to front, causing its antennae to hit each other and sound like a xylophone.

items.name: Kricketune
items.description: The Cricket Pokémon. It crosses its knifelike arms in front of its chest when it cries. It can compose melodies ad lib.

items.name: Shinx
items.description: The Flash Pokémon. All of its fur dazzles if danger is sensed. It flees while the foe is momentarily blinded.

items.name: Luxio
items.description: The Spark Pokémon. Its claws loose electricity with enough amperage to cause fainting. They live in small groups.

items.name: Luxray
items.description: The Gleam Eyes Pokémon. It has eyes that can see through anything. It spots and captures prey hiding behind objects.

items.name: Budew
items.description: The Bud Pokémon. Over the winter, it closes its bud and endures the cold. In spring, the bud opens and releases pollen.

items.name: Roserade
items.description: The Bouquet Pokémon. It attracts prey with a sweet aroma, then downs it with thorny whips hidden in its arms.

items.name: Cranidos
items.description: The Head Butt Pokémon. It lived in jungles around 100 million years ago. Its skull is as hard as iron.

items.name: Rampardos
items.description: The Head Butt Pokémon. Its powerful head butt has enough power to shatter even the most durable things upon impact.

items.name: Shieldon
items.description: The Shield Pokémon. A Pokémon that lived in jungles around 100 million years ago. Its facial hide is extremely hard.

items.name: Bastiodon
items.description: The Shield Pokémon. Any frontal attack is repulsed. It is a docile Pokémon that feeds on grass and berries.

items.name: Burmy
items.description: The Bagworm Pokémon. To shelter itself from cold, wintry winds, it covers itself with a cloak made of twigs and leaves.

items.name: Wormadam Plant Cloak
items.description: The Bagworm Pokémon. When Burmy evolved, its cloak became a part of this Pokémon’s body. The cloak is never shed.

items.name: Wormadam Sand Cloak
items.description: The Bagworm Pokémon. When Burmy evolved, its cloak became a part of this Pokémon’s body. The cloak is never shed.

items.name: Wormadam Trash Cloak
items.description: The Bagworm Pokémon. When Burmy evolved, its cloak became a part of this Pokémon’s body. The cloak is never shed.

items.name: Mothim
items.description: The Moth Pokémon. It loves the honey of flowers and steals honey collected by Combee.

items.name: Combee
items.description: The Tiny Bee Pokémon. A Pokémon formed by three others. It busily carries sweet floral honey to Vespiquen.

items.name: Vespiquen
items.description: The Beehive Pokémon. Its abdomen is a honeycomb for grubs. It raises its grubs on honey collected by Combee.

items.name: Pachirisu
items.description: The EleSquirrel Pokémon. It makes fur balls that crackle with static electricity. It stores them with berries in tree holes.

items.name: Buizel
items.description: The Sea Weasel Pokémon. It has a flotation sac that is like an inflatable collar. It floats on water with its head out.

items.name: Floatzel
items.description: The Sea Weasel Pokémon. It floats using its well-developed flotation sac. It assists in the rescues of drowning people.

items.name: Cherubi
items.description: The Cherry Pokémon. The small ball holds the nutrients needed for evolution. Apparently, it is very sweet and tasty.

items.name: Cherrim
items.description: The Blossom Pokémon. It blooms during times of strong sunlight. It tries to make up for everything it endured as a bud.

items.name: Shellos
items.description: The Sea Slug Pokémon. Its colors and shapes differ from region to region. In the Sinnoh region, two types are confirmed.

items.name: Gastrodon
items.description: The Sea Slug Pokémon. It has a pliable body without any bones. If any part of its body is torn off, it grows right back.

items.name: Ambipom
items.description: The Long Tail Pokémon. To eat, it deftly shucks nuts with its two tails. It rarely uses its arms now.

items.name: Drifloon
items.description: The Balloon Pokémon. A Pokémon formed by the spirits of people and Pokémon. It loves damp, humid seasons.

items.name: Drifblim
items.description: The Blimp Pokémon. It’s drowzy in daytime, but flies off in the evening in big groups. No one knows where they go.

items.name: Buneary
items.description: The Rabbit Pokémon. It slams foes by sharply uncoiling its rolled ears. It stings enough to make a grown-up cry in pain.

items.name: Lopunny
items.description: The Rabbit Pokémon. An extremely cautious Pokémon. It cloaks its body with its fluffy ear fur when it senses danger.

items.name: Mismagius
items.description: The Magical Pokémon. Its cries sound like incantations. Those hearing it are tormented by headaches and hallucinations.

items.name: Honchkrow
items.description: The Big Boss Pokémon. Becoming active at night, it is known to swarm with numerous MURKROW in tow.

items.name: Glameow
items.description: The Catty Pokémon. It claws if displeased and purrs when affectionate. Its fickleness is very popular among some.

items.name: Purugly
items.description: The Tiger Cat Pokémon. It is a brazen brute that barges its way into another Pokémon’s nest and claims it as its own.

items.name: Chingling
items.description: The Bell Pokémon. It emits cries by agitating an orb at the back of its throat. It moves with flouncing hops.

items.name: Stunky
items.description: The Skunk Pokémon. It protects itself by spraying a noxious fluid from its rear. The stench lingers for 24 hours.

items.name: Skuntank
items.description: The Skunk Pokémon. It sprays a vile-smelling fluid from the tip of its tail to attack. Its range is over 160 feet.

items.name: Bronzor
items.description: The Bronze Pokémon. Implements shaped like it were discovered in ancient tombs. It is unknown if they are related.

items.name: Bronzong
items.description: The Bronze Bell Pokémon. One caused a news sensation when it was dug up at a construction site after a 2,000-year sleep.

items.name: Bonsly
items.description: The Bonsai Pokémon. It looks as if it is always crying. It is actually adjusting its body’s fluid levels by eliminating excess.

items.name: Mime Jr.

conditions.value: in a region of typically cool climate

items.description: The Mime Pokémon. It habitually mimics foes. Once mimicked, the foe cannot take its eyes off this Pokémon.

items.name: Happiny
items.description: The Playhouse Pokémon. It loves round white things. It carries an egg-shaped rock in imitation of CHANSEY.

items.name: Chatot
items.description: The Music Note Pokémon. It can learn and speak human words. If they gather, they all learn the same saying.

items.name: Spiritomb
items.description: The Forbidden Pokémon. A Pokémon that was formed by 108 spirits. It is bound to a fissure in an odd keystone.

items.name: Gible
items.description: The Land Shark Pokémon. It nests in small, horizontal holes in cave walls. It pounces to catch prey that stray too close.

items.name: Gabite
items.description: The Cave Pokémon. There is a long-held belief that medicine made from its scales will heal even incurable illnesses.

items.name: Garchomp
items.description: The Mach Pokémon. When it folds up its body and extends its wings, it looks like a jet plane. It flies at sonic speed.

items.name: Munchlax
items.description: The Big Eater Pokémon. It wolfs down its weight in food once a day, swallowing food whole with almost no chewing.

items.name: Riolu
items.description: The Emanation Pokémon. The aura that emanates from its body intensifies to alert others if it is afraid or sad.

items.name: Lucario
items.description: The Aura Pokémon. It has the ability to sense the auras of all things. It understands human speech.

items.name: Hippopotas
items.description: The Hippo Pokémon. It lives in arid places. Instead of perspiration, it expels grainy sand from its body.

items.name: Hippowdon
items.description: The Heavyweight Pokémon. It blasts internally stored sand from ports on its body to create a towering twister for attack.

items.name: Skorupi
items.description: The Scorpion Pokémon. It grips prey with its tail claws and injects poison. It tenaciously hangs on until the poison takes.

items.name: Drapion
items.description: The Ogre Scorpion Pokémon. It has the power in its clawed arms to make scrap of a car. The tips of its claws release poison.

items.name: Croagunk
items.description: The Toxic Mouth Pokémon. Its cheeks hold poison sacs. It tries to catch foes off guard to jab them with toxic fingers.

items.name: Toxicroak
items.description: The Toxic Mouth Pokémon. Its knuckle claws secrete a toxin so vile that even a scratch could prove fatal.

items.name: Carnivine
items.description: The Bug Catcher Pokémon. It attracts prey with its sweet-smelling saliva, then chomps down. It takes a whole day to eat prey.

items.name: Finneon
items.description: The Wing Fish Pokémon. After long exposure to sunlight, the patterns on its tail fins shine vividly when darkness arrives.

items.name: Lumineon
items.description: The Neon Pokémon. It lives on the deep-sea floor. It attracts prey by flashing the patterns on its four tail fins.

items.name: Mantyke

conditions.value: when Remoraid is also in the party

items.description: The Kite Pokémon. A friendly Pokémon that captures the subtle flows of seawater using its two antennae.

items.name: Snover
items.description: The Frost Tree Pokémon. It lives on snowy mountains. Having had little contact with humans, it is boldly inquisitive.

items.name: Abomasnow
items.description: The Frost Tree Pokémon. It whips up blizzards in mountains that are always buried in snow. It is the abominable snowman.

items.name: Weavile
items.description: The Sharp Claw Pokémon. They live in cold regions, forming groups of four or five that hunt prey with impressive coordination.

items.name: Magnezone
items.description: The Magnet Area Pokémon. It evolved from exposure to a special magnetic field. Three units generate magnetism.

items.name: Lickilicky
items.description: The Licking Pokémon. It wraps things with its extensible tongue. Getting too close to it will leave you soaked with drool.

items.name: Rhyperior
items.description: The Drill Pokémon. It puts rocks in holes in its palms and uses its muscles to shoot them. Geodude are shot at rare times.

items.name: Tangrowth
items.description: The Vine Pokémon. It ensnares prey by extending arms made of vines. Losing arms to predators does not trouble it.

items.name: Electivire
items.description: The Thunderbolt Pokémon. It pushes the tips of its two tails against the foe, then lets loose with over 20,000 volts of power.

items.name: Magmortar
items.description: The Blast Pokémon. It blasts fireballs of over 3,600 degrees F from the ends of its arms. It lives in volcanic craters.

items.name: Togekiss
items.description: The Jubilee Pokémon. It will never appear where there is strife. Its sightings have become rare recently.

items.name: Yanmega
items.description: The Ogre Darner Pokémon. By churning its wings, it creates shock waves that inflict critical internal injuries to foes.

items.name: Leafeon
items.description: The Verdant Pokémon. Just like a plant, it uses photosynthesis. As a result, it is always enveloped in clear air.

items.name: Glaceon
items.description: The Fresh Snow Pokémon. As a protective technique, it can completely freeze its fur to make its hairs stand like needles.

items.name: Gliscor
items.description: The Fang Scorpion Pokémon. It observes prey while hanging inverted from branches. When the chance presents itself, it swoops!

items.name: Mamoswine
items.description: The Twin Tusk Pokémon. Its impressive tusks are made of ice. The population thinned when it turned warm after the ice age.

items.name: Porygon-Z
items.description: The Virtual Pokémon. Additional software was installed to make it a better Pokémon. It began acting oddly, however.

items.name: Gallade
items.description: The Blade Pokémon. A master of courtesy and swordsmanship, it fights using extending swords on its elbows.

items.name: Probopass
items.description: The Compass Pokémon. It exudes strong magnetism from all over. It controls three small units called Mini-Noses.

items.name: Dusknoir
items.description: The Gripper Pokémon. The antenna on its head captures radio waves from the world of spirits that command it to take people there.

items.name: Froslass
items.description: The Snow Land Pokémon. It freezes foes with an icy breath nearly -60 degrees F. What seems to be its body is actually hollow.

items.name: Rotom
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Rotom Heat
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Rotom Wash
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Rotom Frost
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Rotom Fan
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Rotom Mow
items.description: The Plasma Pokémon. Its body is composed of plasma. It is known to infiltrate electronic devices and wreak havoc.

items.name: Uxie
items.description: The Knowledge Pokémon. Known as “The Being of Knowledge.” It is said that it can wipe out the memory of those who see its eyes.

items.name: Mesprit
items.description: The Emotion Pokémon. Known as “The Being of Emotion.” It taught humans the nobility of sorrow, pain, and joy.

items.name: Azelf
items.description: The Willpower Pokémon. Known as “The Being of Willpower.” It sleeps at the bottom of a lake to keep the world in balance.

items.name: Dialga
items.description: The Temporal Pokémon. It has the power to control time. It appears in Sinnoh-region myths as an ancient deity.

items.name: Dialga (Origin Forme)
items.description: The Temporal Pokémon. Radiant light caused Dialga to take on a form bearing a striking resemblance to the creator Pokémon. Dialga now wields such colossal strength that one must conclude this is its true form.

items.name: Palkia
items.description: The Spatial Pokémon. It has the ability to distort space. It is described as a deity in Sinnoh-region mythology.

items.name: Palkia (Origin Forme)
items.description: The Spatial Pokémon. It soars across the sky in a form that greatly resembles the creator of all things. Perhaps this imitation of appearance is Palkia’s strategy for gaining Arceus’s powers.

items.name: Heatran
items.description: The Lava Dome Pokémon. It dwells in volcanic caves. It digs in with its cross-shaped feet to crawl on ceilings and walls.

items.name: Regigigas
items.description: The Colossal Pokémon. There is an enduring legend that states this Pokémon towed continents with ropes.

items.name: Giratina Altered Forme
items.description: The Renegade Pokémon. A Pokémon that is said to live in a world on the reverse side of ours. It appears in an ancient cemetery.

items.name: Giratina Origin Forme
items.description: The Renegade Pokémon. A Pokémon that is said to live in a world on the reverse side of ours. It appears in an ancient cemetery.

items.name: Cresselia
items.description: The Lunar Pokémon. Shiny particles are released from its wings like a veil. It is said to represent the crescent moon.

items.name: Phione
items.description: The Sea Drifter Pokémon. A Pokémon that lives in warm seas. It inflates the flotation sac on its head to drift and search for food.

items.name: Manaphy
items.description: The Seafaring Pokémon. Born on a cold seafloor, it will swim great distances to return to its birthplace.

items.name: Darkrai
items.description: The Pitch-Black Pokémon. It can lull people to sleep and make them dream. It is active during nights of the new moon.

items.name: Shaymin Land
items.description: The Gratitude Pokémon. It lives in flower patches and avoids detection by curling up to look like a flowering plant.

items.name: Shaymin Sky
items.description: The Gratitude Pokémon. It lives in flower patches and avoids detection by curling up to look like a flowering plant.

items.name: Arceus
items.description: The Alpha Pokémon. It is described in mythology as the Pokémon that shaped the universe with its 1,000 arms.

items.name: Victini
items.description: The Victory Pokémon. It creates an unlimited supply of energy inside its body, which it shares with those who touch it.

items.name: Snivy
items.description: The Grass Snake Pokémon. They photosynthesize by bathing their tails in sunlight. When they are not feeling well, their tails droop.

items.name: Servine
items.description: The Grass Snake Pokémon. They avoid attacks by sinking into the shadows of thick foliage. They retaliate with masterful whipping techniques.

items.name: Serperior
items.description: The Regal Pokémon. They raise their heads to intimidate opponents but only give it their all when fighting a powerful opponent.

items.name: Tepig
items.description: The Fire Pig Pokémon. It blows fire through its nose. When it catches a cold, the fire becomes pitch-black smoke instead.

items.name: Pignite
items.description: The Fire Pig Pokémon. Whatever it eats becomes fuel for the flame in its stomach. When it is angered, the intensity of the flame increases.

items.name: Emboar
items.description: The Mega Fire Pig Pokémon. It has mastered fast and powerful fighting moves. It grows a beard of fire.

items.name: Oshawott
items.description: The Sea Otter Pokémon. The scalchop on its stomach is made from the same elements as claws. It detaches the scalchop for use as a blade.

items.name: Dewott
items.description: The Discipline Pokémon. Scalchop techniques differ from one Dewott to another. It never neglects maintaining its scalchops.

items.name: Samurott
items.description: The Formidable Pokémon. Part of the armor on its anterior legs becomes a giant sword. Its cry alone is enough to intimidate most enemies.

items.name: Patrat
items.description: The Scout Pokémon. Extremely cautious, they take shifts to maintain a constant watch of their nest. They feel insecure without a lookout.

items.name: Watchog
items.description: The Lookout Pokémon. They make the patterns on their bodies shine in order to threaten predators. Keen eyesight lets them see in the dark.

items.name: Lillipup
items.description: The Puppy Pokémon. The long hair around its face provides an amazing radar that lets it sense subtle changes in its surroundings.

items.name: Herdier
items.description: The Loyal Dog Pokémon. It loyally follows its Trainer's orders. For ages, they have helped Trainers raise Pokémon.

items.name: Stoutland
items.description: The Big-Hearted Pokémon. This extremely wise Pokémon excels at rescuing people stranded at sea or in the mountains.

items.name: Purrloin
items.description: The Devious Pokémon. Its cute act is a ruse. When victims let down their guard, they find their items taken. It attacks with sharp claws.

items.name: Liepard
items.description: The Cruel Pokémon. Stealthily, it sneaks up on its target, striking from behind before its victim has a chance to react.

items.name: Pansage
items.description: The Grass Monkey Pokémon. It shares the leaf on its head with weary-looking Pokémon. These leaves are known to relieve stress.

items.name: Simisage
items.description: The Thorn Monkey Pokémon. It attacks enemies with strikes of its thorn-covered tail. This Pokémon is wild tempered.

items.name: Pansear
items.description: The High Temp Pokémon. This Pokémon lives in caves in volcanoes. The fire within the tuft on its head can reach 600° F.

items.name: Simisear
items.description: The Ember Pokémon. A flame burns inside its body. It scatters embers from its head and tail to sear its opponents.

items.name: Panpour
items.description: The Spray Pokémon. It does not thrive in dry environments. It keeps itself damp by shooting water stored in its head tuft from its tail.

items.name: Simipour
items.description: The Geyser Pokémon. The high-pressure water expelled from its tail is so powerful, it can destroy a concrete wall.

items.name: Munna
items.description: The Dream Eater Pokémon. It eats the dreams of people and Pokémon. When it eats a pleasant dream, it expels pink-colored mist.

items.name: Musharna
items.description: The Drowsing Pokémon. With the mist from its forehead, it can create shapes of things from dreams it has eaten.

items.name: Pidove
items.description: The Tiny Pigeon Pokémon. These Pokémon live in cities. They are accustomed to people. Flocks often gather in parks and plazas.

items.name: Tranquill
items.description: The Wild Pigeon Pokémon. Many people believe that, deep in the forest where Tranquill live, there is a peaceful place where there is no war.

items.name: Unfezant
items.description: The Proud Pokémon. Males have plumage on their heads. They will never let themselves feel close to anyone other than their Trainers.

items.name: Blitzle
items.description: The Electrified Pokémon. When thunderclouds cover the sky, it will appear. It can catch lightning with its mane and store the electricity.

items.name: Zebstrika
items.description: The Thunderbolt Pokémon. This ill-tempered Pokémon is dangerous because when it's angry, it shoots lightning from its mane in all directions.

items.name: Roggenrola
items.description: The Mantle Pokémon. They were discovered a hundred years ago in an earthquake fissure. Inside each one is an energy core.

items.name: Boldore
items.description: The Ore Pokémon. Because its energy was too great to be contained, the energy leaked and formed orange crystals.

items.name: Gigalith
items.description: The Compressed Pokémon. The solar energy absorbed by its body's orange crystals is magnified internally and fired from its mouth.

items.name: Woobat
items.description: The Bat Pokémon. Suction from its nostrils enables it to stick to cave walls during sleep. It leaves a heart-shaped mark behind.

items.name: Swoobat
items.description: The Courting Pokémon. Anyone who comes into contact with the ultrasonic waves emitted by a courting male experiences a positive mood shift.

items.name: Drilbur
items.description: The Mole Pokémon. It makes its way swiftly through the soil by putting both claws together and rotating at high speed.

items.name: Excadrill
items.description: The Subterrene Pokémon. More than 300 feet below the surface, they build mazelike nests. Their activity can be destructive to subway tunnels.

items.name: Audino
items.description: The Hearing Pokémon. Its auditory sense is astounding. It has a radarlike ability to understand its surroundings through slight sounds.

items.name: Timburr
items.description: The Muscular Pokémon. These Pokémon appear at building sites and help out with construction. They always carry squared logs.

items.name: Gurdurr
items.description: The Muscular Pokémon. They strengthen their bodies by carrying steel beams. They show off their big muscles to their friends.

items.name: Conkeldurr
items.description: The Muscular Pokémon. They use concrete pillars as walking canes. They know moves that enable them to swing the pillars freely in battle.

items.name: Tympole
items.description: The Tadpole Pokémon. By vibrating its cheeks, it emits sound waves imperceptible to humans. It uses the rhythm of these sounds to talk.

items.name: Palpitoad
items.description: The Vibration Pokémon. It lives in the water and on land. It uses its long, sticky tongue to capture prey.

items.name: Seismitoad
items.description: The Vibration Pokémon. It increases the power of its punches by vibrating the bumps on its fists. It can turn a boulder to rubble with one punch.

items.name: Throh
items.description: The Judo Pokémon. When they encounter foes bigger than themselves, they try to throw them. They always travel in packs of five.

items.name: Sawk
items.description: The Karate Pokémon. Tying their belts gets them pumped and makes their punches more destructive. Disturbing their training angers them.

items.name: Sewaddle
items.description: The Sewing Pokémon. This Pokémon makes clothes for itself. It chews up leaves and sews them with sticky thread extruded from its mouth.

items.name: Swadloon
items.description: The Leaf-Wrapped Pokémon. It protects itself from the cold by wrapping up in leaves. It stays on the move, eating leaves in forests.

items.name: Leavanny
items.description: The Nurturing Pokémon. It keeps its eggs warm with heat from fermenting leaves. It also uses leaves to make warm wrappings for Sewaddle.

items.name: Venipede
items.description: The Centipede Pokémon. It discovers what is going on around it by using the feelers on its head and tail. It is brutally aggressive.

items.name: Whirlipede
items.description: The Curlipede Pokémon. It is usually motionless, but when attacked, it rotates at high speed and then crashes into its opponent.

items.name: Scolipede
items.description: The Megapede Pokémon. Highly aggressive, it uses the claws near its neck to dig into its opponents and poison them.

items.name: Cottonee
items.description: The Cotton Puff Pokémon. They go wherever the wind takes them. On rainy days, their bodies are heavier, so they take shelter beneath big trees.

items.name: Whimsicott
items.description: The Windveiled Pokémon. Riding whirlwinds, they appear. These Pokémon sneak through gaps into houses and cause all sorts of mischief.

items.name: Petilil
items.description: The Bulb Pokémon. Since they prefer moist, nutrient-rich soil, the areas where Petilil live are known to be good for growing plants.

items.name: Lilligant
items.description: The Flowering Pokémon. The fragrance of the garland on its head has a relaxing effect. It withers if a Trainer does not take good care of it.

items.name: Basculin
items.description: The Hostile Pokémon. Red and blue Basculin usually do not get along, but sometimes members of one school mingle with the other's school.

items.name: Sandile
items.description: The Desert Croc Pokémon. It moves along below the sand's surface, except for its nose and eyes. A dark membrane shields its eyes from the sun.

items.name: Krokorok
items.description: The Desert Croc Pokémon. The special membrane covering its eyes can sense the heat of objects, so it can see its surroundings even in darkness.

items.name: Krookodile
items.description: The Intimidation Pokémon. It can expand the focus of its eyes, enabling it to see objects in the far distance as if it were using binoculars.

items.name: Darumaka
items.description: The Zen Charm Pokémon. Darumaka's droppings are hot, so people used to put them in their clothes to keep themselves warm.

items.name: Darmanitan
items.description: The Blazing Pokémon. When weakened in battle, it transforms into a stone statue. Then it sharpens its mind and fights on mentally.

items.name: Maractus
items.description: The Cactus Pokémon. Arid regions are their habitat. They move rhythmically, making a sound similar to maracas.

items.name: Dwebble
items.description: The Rock Inn Pokémon. It makes a hole in a suitable rock. If that rock breaks, the Pokémon remains agitated until it locates a replacement.

items.name: Crustle
items.description: The Stone Home Pokémon. It possesses legs of enormous strength, enabling it to carry heavy slabs for many days, even when crossing arid land.

items.name: Scraggy
items.description: The Shedding Pokémon. It immediately headbutts anyone that makes eye contact with it. Its skull is massively thick.

items.name: Scrafty
items.description: The Hoodlum Pokémon. It can smash concrete blocks with its kicking attacks. The one with the biggest crest is the group leader.

items.name: Sigilyph
items.description: The Avianoid Pokémon. The guardians of an ancient city, they use their psychic power to attack enemies that invade their territory.

items.name: Yamask
items.description: The Spirit Pokémon. These Pokémon arose from the spirits of people interred in graves in past ages. Each retains memories of its former life.

items.name: Cofagrigus
items.description: The Coffin Pokémon. They pretend to be elaborate coffins to teach lessons to grave robbers. Their bodies are covered in pure gold.

items.name: Tirtouga
items.description: The Prototurtle Pokémon. About 100 million years ago, these Pokémon swam in oceans. It is thought they also went on land to attack prey.

items.name: Carracosta
items.description: The Prototurtle Pokémon. Incredible jaw strength enables them to chew up steel beams and rocks along with their prey.

items.name: Archen
items.description: The First Bird Pokémon. Revived from a fossil, this Pokémon is thought to be the ancestor of all bird Pokémon.

items.name: Archeops
items.description: The First Bird Pokémon. It runs better than it flies. It catches prey by running at speeds comparable to those of an automobile.

items.name: Trubbish
items.description: The Trash Bag Pokémon. The combination of garbage bags and industrial waste caused the chemical reaction that created this Pokémon.

items.name: Garbodor
items.description: The Trash Heap Pokémon. They absorb garbage and make it part of their bodies. They shoot a poisonous liquid from their right-hand fingertips.

items.name: Zorua
items.description: The Tricky Fox Pokémon. To protect themselves from danger, they hide their true identities by transforming into people and Pokémon.

items.name: Zoroark
items.description: The Illusion Fox Pokémon. Each has the ability to fool a large group of people simultaneously. They protect their lair with illusory scenery.

items.name: Minccino
items.description: The Chinchilla Pokémon. These Pokémon prefer a tidy habitat. They are always sweeping and dusting, using their tails as brooms.

items.name: Cinccino
items.description: The Scarf Pokémon. Their white fur feels amazing to touch. Their fur repels dust and prevents static electricity from building up.

items.name: Gothita
items.description: The Fixation Pokémon. They intently observe both Trainers and Pokémon. Apparently, they are looking at something that only Gothita can see.

items.name: Gothorita
items.description: The Manipulate Pokémon. Starlight is the source of their power. At night, they mark star positions by using psychic power to float stones.

items.name: Gothitelle
items.description: The Astral Body Pokémon. They can predict the future from the placement and movement of the stars. They can see Trainers' life spans.

items.name: Solosis
items.description: The Cell Pokémon. Because their bodies are enveloped in a special liquid, they can survive in any environment.

items.name: Duosion
items.description: The Mitosis Pokémon. When their brains, now divided in two, are thinking the same thoughts, these Pokémon exhibit their maximum power.

items.name: Reuniclus
items.description: The Multiplying Pokémon. These remarkably intelligent Pokémon fight by controlling arms that can grip with rock-crushing power.

items.name: Ducklett
items.description: The Water Bird Pokémon. When attacked, it uses its feathers to splash water, escaping under cover of the spray.

items.name: Swanna
items.description: The White Bird Pokémon. It administers sharp, powerful pecks with its bill. It whips its long neck to deliver forceful repeated strikes.

items.name: Vanillite
items.description: The Fresh Snow Pokémon. This Pokémon formed from icicles bathed in energy from the morning sun. It sleeps buried in snow.

items.name: Vanillish
items.description: The Icy Snow Pokémon. It conceals itself from enemy eyes by creating many small ice particles and hiding among them.

items.name: Vanilluxe
items.description: The Snowstorm Pokémon. If both heads get angry simultaneously, this Pokémon expels a blizzard, burying everything in snow.

items.name: Deerling
items.description: The Season Pokémon. The turning of the seasons changes the color and scent of this Pokémon's fur. People use it to mark the seasons.

items.name: Sawsbuck
items.description: The Season Pokémon. The plants growing on its horns change according to the season. The leaders of the herd possess magnificent horns.

items.name: Emolga
items.description: The Sky Squirrel Pokémon. They live on treetops and glide using the inside of a cape-like membrane while discharging electricity.

items.name: Karrablast

conditions.value: while in the presence of a Shelmet

items.description: The Clamping Pokémon. When they feel threatened, they spit an acidic liquid to drive attackers away. This Pokémon targets Shelmet.

items.name: Escavalier
items.description: The Cavalry Pokémon. These Pokémon evolve by wearing the shell covering of a Shelmet. The steel armor protects their whole body.

items.name: Foongus
items.description: The Mushroom Pokémon. For some reason, this Pokémon resembles a Poké Ball. They release poison spores to repel those who try to catch them.

items.name: Amoonguss
items.description: The Mushroom Pokémon. They show off their Poké Ball caps to lure prey, but very few Pokémon are fooled by this.

items.name: Frillish
items.description: The Floating Pokémon. They paralyze prey with poison, then drag them down to their lairs, five miles below the surface.

items.name: Jellicent
items.description: The Floating Pokémon. They propel themselves by expelling absorbed seawater from their bodies. Their favorite food is life energy.

items.name: Alomomola
items.description: The Caring Pokémon. Floating in the open sea is how they live. When they find a wounded Pokémon, they embrace it and bring it to shore.

items.name: Joltik
items.description: The Attaching Pokémon. They attach themselves to large-bodied Pokémon and absorb static electricity, which they store in an electric pouch.

items.name: Galvantula
items.description: The EleSpider Pokémon. They employ an electrically charged web to trap their prey. While it is immobilized by shock, they leisurely consume it.

items.name: Ferroseed
items.description: The Thorn Seed Pokémon. They stick their spikes into cave walls and absorb the minerals they find in the rock.

items.name: Ferrothorn
items.description: The Thorn Pod Pokémon. They attach themselves to cave ceilings, firing steel spikes at targets passing beneath them.

items.name: Klink
items.description: The Gear Pokémon. Interlocking two bodies and spinning around generates the energy they need to live.

items.name: Klang
items.description: The Gear Pokémon. Spinning minigears are rotated at high speed and repeatedly fired away. It is dangerous if the gears don't return.

items.name: Klinklang
items.description: The Gear Pokémon. The gear with the red core is rotated at high speed for a rapid energy charge.

items.name: Tynamo
items.description: The EleFish Pokémon. These Pokémon move in schools. They have an electricity-generating organ, so they discharge electricity if in danger.

items.name: Eelektrik
items.description: The EleFish Pokémon. These Pokémon have a big appetite. When they spot their prey, they attack it and paralyze it with electricity.

items.name: Eelektross
items.description: The EleFish Pokémon. With their sucker mouths, they suck in prey. Then they use their fangs to shock the prey with electricity.

items.name: Elgyem
items.description: The Cerebral Pokémon. This Pokémon had never been seen until it appeared from far in the desert 50 years ago.

items.name: Beheeyem
items.description: The Cerebral Pokémon. It uses psychic power to control an opponent's brain and tamper with its memories.

items.name: Litwick
items.description: The Candle Pokémon. While shining a light and pretending to be a guide, it leeches off the life force of any who follow it.

items.name: Lampent
items.description: The Lamp Pokémon. It arrives near the moment of death and steals spirit from the body.

items.name: Chandelure
items.description: The Luring Pokémon. Being consumed in Chandelure's flame burns up the spirit, leaving the body behind.

items.name: Axew
items.description: The Tusk Pokémon. They mark their territory by leaving gashes in trees with their tusks. If a tusk breaks, a new one grows in quickly.

items.name: Fraxure
items.description: The Axe Jaw Pokémon. Their tusks can shatter rocks. Territory battles between Fraxure can be intensely violent.

items.name: Haxorus
items.description: The Axe Jaw Pokémon. Their sturdy tusks will stay sharp even if used to cut steel beams. These Pokémon are covered in hard armor.

items.name: Cubchoo
items.description: The Chill Pokémon. Its nose is always running. It sniffs the snot back up because the mucus provides the raw material for its moves.

items.name: Beartic
items.description: The Freezing Pokémon. It freezes its breath to create fangs and claws of ice to fight with. Cold northern areas are its habitat.

items.name: Cryogonal
items.description: The Crystallizing Pokémon. They are born in snow clouds. They use chains made of ice crystals to capture prey.

items.name: Shelmet

conditions.value: while in the presence of a Karrablast

items.description: The Snail Pokémon. It evolves when bathed in an electric-like energy along with Karrablast. The reason is still unknown.

items.name: Accelgor
items.description: The Shell Out Pokémon. Having removed its heavy shell, it becomes very light and can fight with ninja-like movements.

items.name: Stunfisk
items.description: The Trap Pokémon. It conceals itself in the mud of the seashore. Then it waits. When prey touch it, it delivers a jolt of electricity.

items.name: Mienfoo
items.description: The Martial Arts Pokémon. They have mastered elegant combos. As they concentrate, their battle moves become swifter and more precise.

items.name: Mienshao
items.description: The Martial Arts Pokémon. They use the long fur on their arms as a whip to strike their opponents.

items.name: Druddigon
items.description: The Cave Pokémon. It races through narrow caves, using its sharp claws to catch prey. The skin on its face is harder than a rock.

items.name: Golett
items.description: The Automaton Pokémon. These Pokémon are thought to have been created by the science of an ancient and mysterious civilization.

items.name: Golurk
items.description: The Automaton Pokémon. It is said that Golurk were ordered to protect people and Pokémon by the ancient people who made them.

items.name: Pawniard
items.description: The Sharp Blade Pokémon. They fight at Bisharp's command. They cling to their prey and inflict damage by sinking their blades into it.

items.name: Bisharp

conditions.value: after defeating an evolution of Pawniard that's holding a Leader's Crest one-on-one, while itself holding a Leader's Crest

items.description: The Sword Blade Pokémon. Bisharp pursues prey in the company of a large group of Pawniard. Then Bisharp finishes off the prey.

items.name: Bouffalant
items.description: The Bash Buffalo Pokémon. They charge wildly and headbutt everything. Their headbutts have enough destructive force to derail a train.

items.name: Rufflet
items.description: The Eaglet Pokémon. They will challenge anything, even strong opponents, without fear. Their frequent fights help them become stronger.

items.name: Braviary
items.description: The Valiant Pokémon. The more scars they have, the more respect these brave soldiers of the sky get from their peers.

items.name: Vullaby
items.description: The Diapered Pokémon. They tend to guard their posteriors with suitable bones they have found. They pursue weak Pokémon.

items.name: Mandibuzz
items.description: The Bone Vulture Pokémon. Watching from the sky, they swoop to strike weakened Pokémon on the ground. They decorate themselves with bones.

items.name: Heatmor
items.description: The Anteater Pokémon. Using their very hot, flame-covered tongues, they burn through Durant's steel bodies and consume their insides.

items.name: Durant
items.description: The Iron Ant Pokémon. Durant dig nests in mountains. They build their complicated, interconnected tunnels into mazes.

items.name: Deino
items.description: The Irate Pokémon. They cannot see, so they tackle and bite to learn about their surroundings. Their bodies are covered in wounds.

items.name: Zweilous
items.description: The Hostile Pokémon. Since their two heads do not get along and compete with each other for food, they always eat too much.

items.name: Hydreigon
items.description: The Brutal Pokémon. The heads on their arms do not have brains. They use all three heads to consume and destroy everything.

items.name: Larvesta
items.description: The Torch Pokémon. The base of volcanoes is where they make their homes. They shoot fire from their five horns to repel attacking enemies.

items.name: Volcarona
items.description: The Sun Pokémon. A sea of fire engulfs the surroundings of their battles, since they use their six wings to scatter their ember scales.

items.name: Cobalion
items.description: The Iron Will Pokémon. It has a body and heart of steel. Its glare is sufficient to make even an unruly Pokémon obey it.

items.name: Terrakion
items.description: The Cavern Pokémon. Its charge is strong enough to break through a giant castle wall in one blow. This Pokémon is spoken of in legends.

items.name: Virizion
items.description: The Grassland Pokémon. Its head sprouts horns as sharp as blades. Using whirlwind-like movements, it confounds and swiftly cuts opponents.

items.name: Tornadus
items.description: The Cyclone Pokémon. Tornadus expels massive energy from its tail, causing severe storms. Its power is great enough to blow houses away.

items.name: Thundurus
items.description: The Bolt Strike Pokémon. The spikes on its tail discharge immense bolts of lightning. It flies around the Unova region firing off lightning bolts.

items.name: Reshiram
items.description: The Vast White Pokémon. When Reshiram's tail flares, the heat energy moves the atmosphere and changes the world's weather.

items.name: Zekrom
items.description: The Deep Black Pokémon. This Pokémon appears in legends. In its tail, it has a giant generator that creates electricity.

items.name: Landorus
items.description: The Abundance Pokémon. The energy that comes pouring from its tail increases the nutrition in the soil, making crops grow to great size.

items.name: Kyurem
items.description: The Boundary Pokémon. It can produce ultracold air. Its body is frozen.

items.name: White Kyurem
items.description: The Boundary Pokémon. It can produce ultracold air. Its body is frozen.

items.name: Black Kyurem
items.description: The Boundary Pokémon. It can produce ultracold air. Its body is frozen.

items.name: Keldeo
items.description: The Colt Pokémon. It crosses the world, running over the surfaces of oceans and rivers. It appears at scenic waterfronts.

items.name: Meloetta - Aria
items.description: The Melody Pokémon. Many famous songs have been inspired by the melodies that Meloetta plays.

items.name: Meloetta - Pirouette
items.description: The Melody Pokémon. Many famous songs have been inspired by the melodies that Meloetta plays.

items.name: Genesect
items.description: The Paleozoic Pokémon. This ancient bug Pokémon was altered by Team Plasma. They upgraded the cannon on its back.

items.name: Chespin
items.description: The Spiny Nut Pokémon. The quills on its head are usually soft. When it flexes them, the points become so hard and sharp that they can pierce rock.

items.name: Quilladin
items.description: The Spiny Armor Pokémon. It relies on its sturdy shell to deflect predators' attacks. It counterattacks with its sharp quills.

items.name: Chesnaught
items.description: The Spiny Armor Pokémon. Its Tackle is forceful enough to flip a 50-ton tank. It shields its allies from danger with its own body.

items.name: Fennekin
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. Eating a twig fills it with energy, and its roomy ears give vent to air hotter than 390 degrees Fahrenheit.

items.name: Braixen
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. It has a twig stuck in its tail. With friction from its tail fur, it sets the twig on fire and launches into battle.

items.name: Delphox
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. It gazes into the flame at the tip of its branch to achieve a focused state, which allows it to see into the future.

items.name: Froakie
items.description: The Bubble Frog Pokémon. It secretes flexible bubbles from its chest and back. The bubbles reduce the damage it would otherwise take when attacked.

items.name: Frogadier
items.description: The Bubble Frog Pokémon. It can throw bubble-covered pebbles with precise control, hitting empty cans up to a hundred feet away.

items.name: Greninja
items.description: The Ninja Pokémon. It creates throwing stars out of compressed water. When it spins them and throws them at high speed, these stars can split metal in two.

items.name: Bunnelby
items.description: The Digging Pokémon. They use their large ears to dig burrows. They will dig the whole night through.

items.name: Diggersby
items.description: The Digging Pokémon. With their powerful ears, they can heft boulders of a ton or more with ease. They can be a big help at construction sites.

items.name: Fletchling
items.description: The Tiny Robin Pokémon. These friendly Pokémon send signals to one another with beautiful chirps and tail-feather movements.

items.name: Fletchinder
items.description: The Ember Pokémon. From its beak, it expels embers that set the tall grass on fire. Then it pounces on the bewildered prey that pop out of the grass.

items.name: Talonflame
items.description: The Scorching Pokémon. In the fever of an exciting battle, it showers embers from the gaps between its feathers and takes to the air.

items.name: Scatterbug
items.description: The Scatterdust Pokémon. When under attack from bird Pokémon, it spews a poisonous black powder that causes paralysis on contact.

items.name: Spewpa
items.description: The Scatterdust Pokémon. It lives hidden within thicket shadows. When predators attack, it quickly bristles the fur covering its body in an effort to threaten them.

items.name: Vivillon
items.description: The Scale Pokémon. Vivillon with many different patterns are found all over the world. These patterns are affected by the climate of their habitat.

items.name: Litleo
items.description: The Lion Cub Pokémon. The stronger the opponent it faces, the more heat surges from its mane and the more power flows through its body.

items.name: Pyroar
items.description: The Royal Pokémon. The male with the largest mane of fire is the leader of the pride.

items.name: Flabébé
items.description: The Single Bloom Pokémon. It draws out and controls the hidden power of flowers. The flower Flabébé holds is most likely part of its body.

items.name: Floette
items.description: The Single Bloom Pokémon. It flutters around fields of flowers and cares for flowers that are starting to wilt. It draws out the hidden power of flowers to battle.

items.name: Florges
items.description: The Garden Pokémon. It claims exquisite flower gardens as its territory, and it obtains power from basking in the energy emitted by flowering plants.

items.name: Skiddo
items.description: The Mount Pokémon. Thought to be one of the first Pokémon to live in harmony with humans, it has a placid disposition.

items.name: Gogoat
items.description: The Mount Pokémon. It can tell how its Trainer is feeling by subtle shifts in the grip on its horns. This empathic sense lets them run as if one being.

items.name: Pancham

conditions.value: its trainer has another dark-type Pokemon in their party

items.description: The Playful Pokémon. It does its best to be taken seriously by its enemies, but its glare is not sufficiently intimidating. Chewing on a leaf is its trademark.

items.name: Pangoro
items.description: The Daunting Pokémon. Although it possesses a violent temperament, it won't put up with bullying. It uses the leaf in its mouth to sense the movements of its enemies.

items.name: Furfrou
items.description: The Poodle Pokémon. Trimming its fluffy fur not only makes it more elegant but also increases the swiftness of its movements.

items.name: Espurr
items.description: The Restraint Pokémon. The organ that emits its intense psychic power is sheltered by its ears to keep power from leaking out.

items.name: Meowstic ♂
items.description: The Constraint Pokémon. When in danger, it raises its ears and releases enough psychic power to grind a 10-ton truck into dust.

items.name: Meowstic ♀
items.description: The Constraint Pokémon. When in danger, it raises its ears and releases enough psychic power to grind a 10-ton truck into dust.

items.name: Honedge
items.description: The Sword Pokémon. Apparently this Pokémon is born when a departed spirit inhabits a sword. It attaches itself to people and drinks their life force.

items.name: Doublade
items.description: The Sword Pokémon. When Honedge evolves, it divides into two swords, which cooperate via telepathy to coordinate attacks and slash their enemies to ribbons.

items.name: Aegislash
items.description: The Royal Sword Pokémon. Generations of kings were attended by these Pokémon, which used their spectral power to manipulate and control people and Pokémon.

items.name: Spritzee
items.description: The Perfume Pokémon. It emits a scent that enraptures those who smell it. This fragrance changes depending on what it has eaten.

items.name: Aromatisse
items.description: The Fragrance Pokémon. It devises various scents, pleasant and unpleasant, and emits scents that its enemies dislike in order to gain an edge in battle.

items.name: Swirlix
items.description: The Cotton Candy Pokémon. To entangle its opponents in battle, it extrudes white threads as sweet and sticky as cotton candy.

items.name: Slurpuff
items.description: The Meringue Pokémon. It can distinguish the faintest of scents. It puts its sensitive sense of smell to use by helping pastry chefs in their work.

items.name: Inkay
items.description: The Revolving Pokémon. Opponents who stare at the flashing of the light-emitting spots on its body become dazed and lose their will to fight.

items.name: Malamar
items.description: The Overturning Pokémon. It wields the most compelling hypnotic powers of any Pokémon, and it forces others to do whatever it wants.

items.name: Binacle
items.description: The Two-Handed Pokémon. Two Binacle live together on one rock. When they fight, one of them will move to a different rock.

items.name: Barbaracle
items.description: The Collective Pokémon. When they evolve, two Binacle multiply into seven. They fight with the power of seven Binacle.

items.name: Skrelp
items.description: The Mock Kelp Pokémon. Camouflaged as rotten kelp, they spray liquid poison on prey that approaches unawares and then finish it off.

items.name: Dragalge
items.description: The Mock Kelp Pokémon. Their poison is strong enough to eat through the hull of a tanker, and they spit it indiscriminately at anything that enters their territory.

items.name: Clauncher
items.description: The Water Gun Pokémon. They knock down flying prey by firing compressed water from their massive claws like shooting a pistol.

items.name: Clawitzer
items.description: The Howitzer Pokémon. Their enormous claws launch cannonballs of water powerful enough to pierce tanker hulls.

items.name: Helioptile
items.description: The Generator Pokémon. They make their home in deserts. They can generate their energy from basking in the sun, so eating food is not a requirement.

items.name: Heliolisk
items.description: The Generator Pokémon. They flare their frills and generate energy. A single Heliolisk can generate sufficient electricity to power a skyscraper.

items.name: Tyrunt
items.description: The Royal Heir Pokémon. This Pokémon was restored from a fossil. If something happens that it doesn't like, it throws a tantrum and runs wild.

items.name: Tyrantrum
items.description: The Despot Pokémon. Thanks to its gargantuan jaws, which could shred thick metal plates as if they were paper, it was invincible in the ancient world it once inhabited.

items.name: Amaura
items.description: The Tundra Pokémon. This ancient Pokémon was restored from part of its body that had been frozen in ice for over 100 million years.

items.name: Aurorus
items.description: The Tundra Pokémon. The diamond-shaped crystals on its body expel air as cold as -240 degrees Fahrenheit, surrounding its enemies and encasing them in ice.

items.name: Sylveon
items.description: The Intertwining Pokémon. It sends a soothing aura from its ribbonlike feelers to calm fights.

items.name: Hawlucha
items.description: The Wrestling Pokémon. Although its body is small, its proficient fighting skills enable it to keep up with big bruisers like Machamp and Hariyama.

items.name: Dedenne
items.description: The Antenna Pokémon. Its whiskers serve as antennas. By sending and receiving electrical waves, it can communicate with others over vast distances.

items.name: Carbink
items.description: The Jewel Pokémon. Born from the temperatures and pressures deep underground, it fires beams from the stone in its head.

items.name: Goomy
items.description: The Soft Tissue Pokémon. The weakest Dragon-type Pokémon, it lives in damp, shady places, so its body doesn't dry out.

items.name: Sliggoo
items.description: The Soft Tissue Pokémon. It drives away opponents by excreting a sticky liquid that can dissolve anything. Its eyes devolved, so it can't see anything.

items.name: Goodra
items.description: The Dragon Pokémon. This very friendly Dragon-type Pokémon will hug its beloved Trainer, leaving that Trainer covered in sticky slime.

items.name: Klefki
items.description: The Key Ring Pokémon. These key collectors threaten any attackers by fiercely jingling their keys at them.

items.name: Phantump
items.description: The Stump Pokémon. These Pokémon are created when spirits possess rotten tree stumps. They prefer to live in abandoned forests.

items.name: Trevenant
items.description: The Elder Tree Pokémon. It can control trees at will. It will trap people who harm the forest, so they can never leave.

items.name: Pumpkaboo
items.description: The Pumpkin Pokémon. The pumpkin body is inhabited by a spirit trapped in this world. As the sun sets, it becomes restless and active.
items.specialAbilityText: Pumpkaboo come in a variety of sizes: Small, Average, Large, and Supersize (All considered "Small" for D&D). The stat block above is for its Small variety. For each size above Small, decrease its DEX by -1 and raise its CON by +1.

items.name: Gourgeist
items.description: The Pumpkin Pokémon. Singing in eerie voices, they wander town streets on the night of the new moon. Anyone who hears their song is cursed.
items.specialAbilityText: Gourgeist come in a variety of sizes: Small, Average, Large, and Supersize (All considered "Small" for D&D, except for Supersize, which is considered "Medium"). The stat block above is for its Small variety. For each size above Small, decrease its DEX by -1 and raise its CON by +1.

items.name: Bergmite
items.description: The Ice Chunk Pokémon. It blocks opponents' attacks with the ice that shields its body. It uses cold air to repair any cracks with new ice.

items.name: Avalugg
items.description: The Iceberg Pokémon. Its ice-covered body is as hard as steel. Its cumbersome frame crushes anything that stands in its way.

items.name: Noibat
items.description: The Sound Wave Pokémon. They live in pitch-black caves. Their enormous ears can emit ultrasonic waves of 200,000 hertz.

items.name: Noivern
items.description: The Sound Wave Pokémon. They fly around on moonless nights and attack careless prey. Nothing can beat them in a battle in the dark.

items.name: Xerneas
items.description: The Life Pokémon. Legends say it can share eternal life. It slept for a thousand years in the form of a tree before its revival.

items.name: Yveltal
items.description: The Destruction Pokémon. When this legendary Pokémon's wings and tail feathers spread wide and glow red, it absorbs the life force of living creatures.

items.name: Zygarde 10% Forme
items.description: The Order Pokémon. Its sharp fangs make short work of finishing off its enemies, but it's unable to maintain this body indefinitely. After a period of time, it falls apart.

items.name: Zygarde 50% Forme
items.description: The Order Pokémon. This is Zygarde's form when it has gathered 50% of its cells. It wipes out all those who oppose it, showing not a shred of mercy.

items.name: Zygarde Complete Forme
items.description: The Order Pokémon. This is Zygarde's form at times when it uses its overwhelming power to suppress those who endanger the ecosystem.

items.name: Diancie
items.description: The Jewel Pokémon. A sudden transformation of Carbink, its pink, glimmering body is said to be the loveliest sight in the whole world.

items.name: Hoopa Confined
items.description: The Mischief Pokémon. In its true form, it possesses a huge amount of power. Legends of its avarice tell how it once carried off an entire castle to gain the treasure hidden within.

items.name: Hoopa Unbound
items.description: The Mischief Pokémon. In its true form, it possesses a huge amount of power. Legends of its avarice tell how it once carried off an entire castle to gain the treasure hidden within.

items.name: Volcanion
items.description: The Steam Pokémon. It lets out billows of steam and disappears into the dense fog. It's said to live in mountains where humans do not tread.

items.name: Alolan Rattata
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. Night after night, they sneak into people’s homes seeking food. A massive outbreak of them has become an issue of public concern.

items.name: Alolan Raticate
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. It has an incredibly greedy personality. Its nest is filled with so much food gathered by Rattata at its direction, it can’t possibly eat it all.

items.name: Alolan Raichu
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. It loves pancakes prepared with a secret Alolan recipe. Some wonder whether that recipe holds the key to this Pokémon’s evolution.

items.name: Alolan Sandshrew
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. An ancient tradition of Alolan festivals, still carried on to this day, is a competition to slide Sandshrew across ice as far as one can.

items.name: Alolan Sandslash
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. It uses large, hooked claws to cut a path through deep snow as it runs. On snowy mountains, this Sandslash is faster than any other Pokémon.

items.name: Alolan Vulpix
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. If you carelessly approach it because it’s cute, the boss of the pack, Ninetales, will appear and freeze you.

items.name: Alolan Ninetales
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. The reason it guides people all the way down to the mountain’s base is that it wants them to hurry up and leave.

items.name: Alolan Diglett
items.description: The Mole Pokémon. Its three hairs change shape depending on Diglett’s mood. When in communication with its comrades, its whiskers wobble to and fro.

items.name: Alolan Dugtrio
items.description: The Mole Pokémon. Its shining gold hair provides it with protection. It’s reputed that keeping any of its fallen hairs will bring bad luck.

items.name: Alolan Meowth
items.description: The Scratch Cat Pokémon. When its delicate pride is wounded, or when the gold coin on its forehead is dirtied, it flies into a hysterical rage.

items.name: Alolan Persian
items.description: The Classy Cat Pokémon. It looks down on everyone other than itself. Its preferred tactics are sucker punches and blindside attacks.

items.name: Alolan Geodude
items.description: The Rock Pokémon. Its stone head is imbued with electricity and magnetism. If you carelessly step on one, you’ll be in for a painful shock.

items.name: Alolan Graveler
items.description: The Rock Pokémon. They eat rocks and often get into a scrap over them. The shock of Graveler smashing together causes a flash of light and a booming noise.

items.name: Alolan Golem
items.description: The Megaton Pokémon. Because it can’t fire boulders at a rapid pace, it’s been known to seize nearby Geodude and fire them from its back.

items.name: Alolan Grimer
items.description: The Sludge Pokémon. Brought to Alola to solve the garbage problem, Grimer seems to relish any and all kinds of trash.

items.name: Alolan Muk
items.description: The Sludge Pokémon. While it’s unexpectedly quiet and friendly, if it’s not fed any trash for a while, it will smash its Trainer’s furnishings and eat up the fragments.

items.name: Alolan Exeggutor
items.description: The Coconut Pokémon. As it grew taller and taller, it outgrew its reliance on psychic powers, while within it awakened the power of the sleeping dragon.

items.name: Alolan Marowak
items.description: The Bone Keeper Pokémon. The bones it possesses were once its mother’s. Its mother’s regrets have become like a vengeful spirit protecting this Pokémon.

items.name: Rowlet
items.description: The Grass Quill Pokémon. It sends its feathers, which are as sharp as blades, flying in attack. Its legs are strong, so its kicks are also formidable.

items.name: Dartrix
items.description: The Blade Quill Pokémon. This narcissistic Pokémon is a clean freak. If you don’t groom it diligently, it will stop listening to you.

items.name: Decidueye
items.description: The Arrow Quill Pokémon. It nocks its arrow quills and shoots them at opponents. When it simply can’t afford to miss, it tugs the vine on its head to improve its focus.

items.name: Litten
items.description: The Fire Cat Pokémon. If you try too hard to get close to it, it won’t open up to you. Even if you do grow close, giving it too much affection is still a no-no.

items.name: Torracat
items.description: The Fire Cat Pokémon. It can act spoiled if it grows close to its Trainer. A powerful Pokémon, its sharp claws can leave its Trainer’s whole body covered in scratches.

items.name: Incineroar
items.description: The Heel Pokémon. Although it’s rough mannered and egotistical, it finds beating down unworthy opponents boring. It gets motivated for stronger opponents.

items.name: Popplio
items.description: The Sea Lion Pokémon. The balloons it inflates with its nose grow larger and larger as it practices day by day.

items.name: Brionne
items.description: The Pop Star Pokémon. It gets excited when it sees a dance it doesn’t know. This hard worker practices diligently until it can learn that dance.

items.name: Primarina
items.description: The Soloist Pokémon. To Primarina, every battle is a stage. It takes down its prey with beautiful singing and dancing.

items.name: Pikipek
items.description: The Woodpecker Pokémon. It pecks at trees with its hard beak. You can get some idea of its mood or condition from the rhythm of its pecking.

items.name: Trumbeak
items.description: The Bugle Beak Pokémon. It can bend the tip of its beak to produce over a hundred different cries at will.

items.name: Toucannon
items.description: The Cannon Pokémon. They smack beaks with others of their kind to communicate. The strength and number of hits tell each other how they feel.

items.name: Yungoos
items.description: The Loitering Pokémon. Its stomach takes up most of its long torso. It’s a big eater, so the amount Trainers have to spend on its food is no laughing matter.

items.name: Gumshoos
items.description: The Stakeout Pokémon. Although it wasn’t originally found in Alola, this Pokémon was brought over a long time ago when there was a huge Rattata outbreak.

items.name: Grubbin
items.description: The Larva Pokémon. If you find its nest, you shouldn’t stick your hand inside. You’ll get bitten by an irritated Grubbin.

items.name: Charjabug
items.description: The Battery Pokémon. It buries itself in fallen leaves and barely moves, munching away on humus. If you accidentally step on one, you’ll get a shock!

items.name: Vikavolt
items.description: The Stag Beetle Pokémon. It has an organ that generates electricity in its abdomen. It concentrates energy in its strong jaws and fires off powerful jolts of electricity.

items.name: Crabrawler
items.description: The Boxing Pokémon. Its hard pincers are well suited to both offense and defense. Fights between two Crabrawler are like boxing matches.

items.name: Crabominable
items.description: The Woolly Crab Pokémon. It stores coldness in its pincers and pummels its foes. It can even smash thick walls of ice to bits!

items.name: Oricorio Baile Style
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. It wins the hearts of its enemies with its passionate dancing and then uses the opening it creates to burn them up with blazing flames.

items.name: Oricorio Pom-Pom Style
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. It lifts its opponents’ spirits with its cheerful dance moves. When they let their guard down, it electrocutes them with a jolt.

items.name: Oricorio Pa'u Style
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. It relaxes its opponents with its elegant dancing. When they let their guard down, it showers them with psychic energy.

items.name: Oricorio Sensu Style
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. It charms its opponents with its refined dancing. When they let their guard down, it places a curse on them that will bring on their demise.

items.name: Cutiefly
items.description: The Bee Fly Pokémon. Nectar and pollen are its favorite fare. In fields of flowers, it gets into skirmishes with Butterfree over food.

items.name: Ribombee
items.description: The Bee Fly Pokémon. Rain makes pollen damp, so Ribombee hates rain. When it sees ominous clouds, it finds a hollow in a tree, where it waits stock-still.

items.name: Rockruff
items.description: The Puppy Pokémon. As they develop, their disposition grows more violent and aggressive. Many Trainers find them too much to handle and abandon them.

items.name: Lycanroc Midday Form
items.description: The Wolf Pokémon. The sharp rocks in its mane can cut like knives. Lycanroc wears its prey down by degrees before finishing them off.

items.name: Lycanroc Midnight Form
items.description: The Wolf Pokémon. It has no problem ignoring orders it doesn’t like. It doesn’t seem to mind getting hurt at all—as long as it can finish off its opponent.

items.name: Lycanroc Dusk Form
items.description: The Wolf Pokémon. Bathed in the setting sun of evening, Lycanroc has undergone a special kind of evolution. An intense fighting spirit underlies its calmness.

items.name: Wishiwashi Solo Form
items.description: The Small Fry Pokémon. They’re weak, so they move in schools. However, they can also often be seen all alone, having strayed from the school.

items.name: Wishiwashi School Form
items.description: The Small Fry Pokémon. Wishiwashi assemble in this formation to face off against strong foes. It boasts a strength that earned it the name “demon of the sea.”

items.name: Mareanie
items.description: The Brutal Star Pokémon. They eat Corsola branches, so Mareanie are hated by craftsmen who work with Corsola branches that have naturally fallen off.

items.name: Toxapex
items.description: The Brutal Star Pokémon. To attack, this Pokémon sends toxic spikes flying at its enemies. Ones that come close get mown down by the claws on its feet.

items.name: Mudbray
items.description: The Donkey Pokémon. It loves playing in the mud. If it isn’t showered with mud on a daily basis, it gets stressed out and stops listening to its Trainer.

items.name: Mudsdale
items.description: The Draft Horse Pokémon. It remains calm and unmoving no matter the situation. It mixes dirt with the saliva in its mouth to make a special kind of mud.

items.name: Dewpider
items.description: The Water Bubble Pokémon. When two Dewpider meet, they display their water bubbles to each other. Then the one with the smaller bubble gets out of the other’s way.

items.name: Araquanid
items.description: The Water Bubble Pokémon. It usually passes its time in the water. When its belly is full, it stores its subdued prey in the water bubble on its head.

items.name: Fomantis
items.description: The Sickle Grass Pokémon. When the sun rises, Fomantis spreads its four leaves and bathes in the sunlight. The tip of its head has a pleasant aroma.

items.name: Lurantis
items.description: The Bloom Sickle Pokémon. For self-protection, it pretends to be a bug Pokémon. Both of its arms bear keen-edged petals.

items.name: Morelull
items.description: The Illuminating Pokémon. It scatters its shining spores around itself. Even though they’re dangerous, nighttime tours of forests where Morelull live are popular.

items.name: Shiinotic
items.description: The Illuminating Pokémon. It puts its prey to sleep and siphons off their vitality through the tip of its arms. If one of its kind is weakened, it helps by sending it vitality.

items.name: Salandit
items.description: The Toxic Lizard Pokémon. The males will do whatever the females tell them. They give the females most of their food. Due to malnutrition, the males can’t evolve.

items.name: Salazzle
items.description: The Toxic Lizard Pokémon. Salazzle lives deep in caves and forces the Salandit it has attracted with its pheromones to serve it.

items.name: Stufful
items.description: The Flailing Pokémon. It boasts power enough to split large trees in half. The organ on its rear releases an odor that it uses to communicate with others of its kind.

items.name: Bewear
items.description: The Strong Arm Pokémon. It waves its hands wildly in intimidation and warning. Life is over for anyone who doesn’t run away as fast as possible.

items.name: Bounsweet
items.description: The Fruit Pokémon. Because of its sweet, delicious aroma, bird Pokémon are always after it, but it’s not intelligent enough to care.

items.name: Steenee
items.description: The Fruit Pokémon. It’s protected by its hard sepals, so it plays with bird Pokémon without worry. They peck it relentlessly, but it doesn’t care.

items.name: Tsareena
items.description: The Fruit Pokémon. A master of grand and beautiful kicks, it can knock out even kickboxing champions with a single blow.

items.name: Comfey
items.description: The Posy Picker Pokémon. It stretches sticky vines out from its head and picks flowers to adorn itself with. When it doesn’t have any flowers, it feels uneasy.

items.name: Oranguru
items.description: The Sage Pokémon. It normally spends its time meditating in the treetops. It throws Poké Balls and gives other Pokémon orders as it pleases.

items.name: Passimian
items.description: The Teamwork Pokémon. They use their saliva to stick leaves to their shoulders. You can tell what troop they belong to from the position of the leaves.

items.name: Wimpod
items.description: The Turn Tail Pokémon. It will pick up anything it finds on the ground. Sometimes it finds coins, so Murkrow and Meowth will go after it.

items.name: Golisopod
items.description: The Hard Scale Pokémon. The shell covering its body is as hard as diamond. This Pokémon will do anything it takes to win.

items.name: Sandygast
items.description: The Sand Heap Pokémon. It likes the shovel on its head, so Sandygast will get serious and fight any children who come to take it back.

items.name: Palossand
items.description: The Sand Castle Pokémon. Each of its grains of sand has its own will. Palossand eats small Pokémon and siphons away their vital essence while they’re still alive.

items.name: Pyukumuku
items.description: The Sea Cucumber Pokémon. The tradition known as Pyukumuku chucking started from the custom of throwing Pyukumuku back into the sea after they wash onshore.

items.name: Type: Null
items.description: The Synthetic Pokémon. A Pokémon weapon developed for a specific mission, it went berserk during an experiment, so it was cryogenically frozen.

items.name: Silvally
items.description: The Synthetic Pokémon. This is its form once it has awakened and evolved. Freed from its heavy mask, its speed is greatly increased.

items.name: Minior Meteor Form
items.description: The Meteor Pokémon. It lives in the ozone layer, where it becomes food for stronger Pokémon. When it tries to run away, it falls to the ground.

items.name: Minior Core Form
items.description: The Meteor Pokémon. Places where Minior fall from the night sky are few and far between, with Alola being one of the precious few.

items.name: Komala
items.description: The Drowsing Pokémon. It stays asleep from the moment it’s born. When it falls into a deep sleep, it stops moving altogether.

items.name: Turtonator
items.description: The Blast Turtle Pokémon. It lives in volcanoes and eats sulfur and other minerals. Materials from the food it eats form the basis of its explosive shell.

items.name: Togedemaru
items.description: The Roly-Poly Pokémon. When it’s surprised or agitated, the 14 fur spikes on its back will stand up involuntarily.

items.name: Mimikyu
items.description: The Disguise Pokémon. It stands in front of a mirror, trying to fix its broken neck as if its life depended on it. It has a hard time getting it right, so it’s crying inside.

items.name: Bruxish
items.description: The Gnash Teeth Pokémon. It burrows beneath the sand, radiating psychic power from the protuberance on its head. It waits for prey as it surveys the area.

items.name: Drampa
items.description: The Placid Pokémon. If a child it has made friends with is bullied, Drampa will find the bully’s house and burn it to the ground.

items.name: Dhelmise
items.description: The Sea Creeper Pokémon. It wraps its prey in green seaweed and sucks away their vitality. It only likes to go after big prey like Wailord.

items.name: Jangmo-o
items.description: The Scaly Pokémon. It smacks the scales on its head against rocks or against the ground to frighten its opponents. It can also contact its friends with these noises.

items.name: Hakamo-o
items.description: The Scaly Pokémon. It makes noise by clanging its scales together. When the rhythm has reached its peak, Hakamo-o attacks.

items.name: Kommo-o
items.description: The Scaly Pokémon. When it howls after finishing off its prey, the metallic sounds of its celebrating comrades can be heard from all around.

items.name: Tapu Koko
items.description: The Land Spirit Pokémon. Although it’s called a guardian deity, if a person or Pokémon puts it in a bad mood, it will become a malevolent deity and attack.

items.name: Tapu Lele
items.description: The Land Spirit Pokémon. As it flutters about, it scatters its strangely glowing scales. Touching them is said to restore good health on the spot.

items.name: Tapu Bulu
items.description: The Land Spirit Pokémon. Although it’s called a guardian deity, it’s violent enough to crush anyone it sees as an enemy.

items.name: Tapu Fini
items.description: The Land Spirit Pokémon. This guardian deity of Poni Island manipulates water. Because it lives deep within a thick fog, it came to be both feared and revered.

items.name: Cosmog
items.description: The Nebula Pokémon. Even though its helpless, gaseous body can be blown away by the slightest breeze, it doesn’t seem to care.

items.name: Cosmoem
items.description: The Protostar Pokémon. The king who ruled Alola in times of antiquity called it the “cocoon of the stars” and built an altar to worship it.

items.name: Solgaleo
items.description: The Sunne Pokémon. Sometimes the result of its opening an Ultra Wormhole is that energy and life-forms from other worlds are called here to this world.

items.name: Lunala
items.description: The Moone Pokémon. Records of it exist in writings from long, long ago, where it was known by the name “the beast that calls the moon.”

items.name: Nihilego
items.description: The Parasite Pokémon. A life-form from another world, it was dubbed an Ultra Beast and is thought to produce a strong neurotoxin.

items.name: Buzzwole
items.description: The Swollen Pokémon. Although it’s alien to this world and a danger here, it’s apparently a common organism in the world where it normally lives.

items.name: Pheromosa
items.description: The Lissome Pokémon. A life-form that lives in another world, its body is thin and supple, but it also possesses great power.

items.name: Xurkitree
items.description: The Glowing Pokémon. Although it’s alien to this world and a danger here, it’s apparently a common organism in the world where it normally lives.

items.name: Celesteela
items.description: The Launch Pokémon. One kind of Ultra Beast. Witnesses have seen it burn down a forest by expelling gas from its two arms.

items.name: Kartana
items.description: The Drawn Sword Pokémon. This Ultra Beast’s body, which is as thin as paper, is like a sharpened sword.

items.name: Guzzlord
items.description: The Junkivore Pokémon. Although it’s alien to this world and a danger here, it’s apparently a common organism in the world where it normally lives.

items.name: Necrozma
items.description: The Prism Pokémon. It looks somehow pained as it rages around in search of light, which serves as its energy. It’s apparently from another world.

items.name: Dusk Mane Necrozma
items.description: The Prism Pokémon. This is Necrozma’s form while it’s absorbing the power of Solgaleo, making it extremely ferocious and impossible to control.

items.name: Dawn Wings Necrozma
items.description: The Prism Pokémon. This is its form while it’s devouring the light of Lunala. It grasps foes in its giant claws and rips them apart with brute force.

items.name: Ultra Necrozma
items.description: The Prism Pokémon. The light pouring out from all over its body affects living things and nature, impacting them in various ways.

items.name: Magearna
items.description: The Artificial Pokémon. It synchronizes its consciousness with others to understand their feelings. This faculty makes it useful for taking care of people.
