items.name: Marshadow
items.description: The Gloomdweller Pokémon. It slips into the shadows of others and mimics their powers and movements. As it improves, it becomes stronger than those it’s imitating.

items.name: Poipole
items.description: The Poison Pin Pokémon. An Ultra Beast that lives in a different world, it cackles wildly as it sprays its opponents with poison from the needles on its head.

items.name: Naganadel
items.description: The Poison Pin Pokémon. One kind of Ultra Beast, it fires a glowing, venomous liquid from its needles. This liquid is also immensely adhesive.

items.name: Stakataka
items.description: The Rampart Pokémon. It appeared from an Ultra Wormhole. Each one appears to be made up of many life-forms stacked one on top of each other.

items.name: Blacephalon
items.description: The Fireworks Pokémon. It slithers toward people. Then, without warning, it triggers the explosion of its own head. It’s apparently one kind of Ultra Beast.

items.name: Zeraora
items.description: The Thunderclap Pokémon. It electrifies its claws and tears its opponents apart with them. Even if they dodge its attack, they’ll be electrocuted by the flying sparks.

items.name: Meltan
items.description: The Hex Nut Pokémon. It dissolves and eats metal. Circulating liquid metal within its body is how it generates energy.

items.name: Melmetal
items.description: The Hex Nut Pokémon. At the end of its life-span, Melmetal will rust and fall apart. The small shards left behind will eventually be reborn as Meltan.

items.name: Galarian Meowth
items.description: The Scratch Cat Pokémon. Living with a savage, seafaring people has toughened this Pokémon's body so much that parts of it have turned to iron.

items.name: Galarian Ponyta
items.description: The Unique Horn Pokémon. Its small horn hides a healing power. With a few rubs from this Pokémon's horn, any slight wound you have will be healed.

items.name: Galarian Rapidash
items.description: The Unique Horn Pokémon. Fearless and proud, Rapidash uses Psychic powers stored in the flowing fur above its hooves to dash through the forest with ease.

items.name: Galarian Slowpoke
items.description: The Dopey Pokémon. Although this Pokémon is normally zoned out, its expression abruptly sharpens on occasion. The cause for this seems to lie in Slowpoke's diet.

items.name: Galarian Slowbro
items.description: The Hermit Crab Pokémon. A Shellder bite set off a chemical reaction with the spices inside Slowbro's body, causing Slowbro to become a Poison-type Pokémon.

items.name: Galarian Farfetch'd

conditions.value: after enduring a single battle where it lands three critical hits

items.description: The Wild Duck Pokémon. Farfetch'd always carries a leek that is twice as long and heavy as its own body and never lets go.

items.name: Galarian Weezing
items.description: The Poison Gas Pokémon. This Pokémon consumes particles that contaminate the air. Instead of leaving droppings, it expels clean air.

items.name: Galarian Mr. Mime
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. Its talent is tap-dancing. It can also manipulate temperatures to create a floor of ice, which this Pokémon can kick up to use as a barrier.

items.name: Galarian Articuno
items.description: The Cruel Pokémon. Its feather-like blades are composed of psychic energy and can shear through thick iron sheets as if they were paper.

items.name: Galarian Zapdos
items.description: The Strong Legs Pokémon. One kick from its powerful legs will pulverize a dump truck. Supposedly, this Pokémon runs through the mountains at over 180 mph.

items.name: Galarian Moltres
items.description: The Malevolent Pokémon. This Pokémon’s sinister, flame-like aura will consume the spirit of any creature it hits. Victims become burned-out shadows of themselves.

items.name: Galarian Slowking
items.description: The Hexpert Pokémon. A combination of toxins and the shock of evolving has increased Shellder's intelligence to the point that Shellder now controls Slowking.

items.name: Galarian Corsola
items.description: The Coral Pokémon. Sudden climate change wiped out this ancient kind of Corsola. This Pokémon absorbs others' life-force through its branches.

items.name: Galarian Zigzagoon
items.description: The Tiny Raccoon Pokémon. Its restlessness has it constantly running around. If it sees another Pokémon, it will purposely run into them in order to start a fight.

items.name: Galarian Linoone
items.description: The Rushing Pokémon. It uses its long tongue to taunt opponents. Once the opposition is enraged, this Pokémon hurls itself at the opponent, tackling them forcefully.

items.name: Galarian Darumaka
items.description: The Zen Charm Pokémon. It lived in snowy areas for so long that its fire sac cooled off and atrophied. It now has an organ that generates cold instead.

items.name: Galarian Darmanitan
items.description: The Zen Mode Pokémon. On days when blizzards blow through, it comes down to where people live. It stashes food in the snowball on its head, taking it home for later.

items.name: Galarian Yamask
items.description: The Spirit Pokémon. A clay slab with cursed engravings took possession of a Yamask. The slab is said to be absorbing the Yamask's dark power.

items.name: Galarian Stunfisk
items.description: The Trap Pokémon. Its conspicuous lips lure prey in as it lies in wait in the mud. When prey gets close, Stunfisk clamps its jagged steel fins down on them.

items.name: Grookey
items.description: The Chimp Pokémon. Grookey attacks by beating with a stick. As the speed of its beats increases, Grookey's excitement does too.

items.name: Thwackey
items.description: The Beat Pokémon. The faster a Thwackey can beat out a rhythm with its two sticks, the more respect it wins from its peers.

items.name: Rillaboom
items.description: The Drummer Pokémon. By drumming, it taps into the power of its special tree stump. The roots of the stump follow its direction in battle.

items.name: Scorbunny
items.description: The Rabbit Pokémon. A warm-up of running around gets fire energy coursing through this Pokémon's body. Once that happens, it's ready to fight at full power.

items.name: Raboot
items.description: The Rabbit Pokémon. It kicks berries right off the branches of trees and then juggles them with its feet, practicing its footwork.

items.name: Cinderace
items.description: The Striker Pokémon. It juggles a pebble with its feet, turning it into a burning soccer ball. Its shots strike opponents hard and leave them scorched.

items.name: Sobble
items.description: The Water Lizard Pokémon. When scared, this Pokémon cries. Its tears pack the chemical punch of 100 onions, and attackers won't be able to resist weeping.

items.name: Drizzile
items.description: The Water Lizard Pokémon. A clever combatant, this Pokémon battles using water balloons created with moisture secreted from its palms.

items.name: Inteleon
items.description: The Secret Agent Pokémon. It has many hidden capabilities, such as fingertips that can shoot water and a membrane on its back that it can use to glide through the air.

items.name: Skwovet
items.description: The Cheeky Pokémon. It eats berries nonstop—a habit that has made it more resilient than it looks. It'll show up on farms, searching for yet more berries.

items.name: Greedent
items.description: The Greedy Pokémon. It stashes berries in its tail—so many berries that they fall out constantly. But this Pokémon is a bit slow-witted, so it doesn't notice the loss.

items.name: Rookidee
items.description: The Tiny Bird Pokémon. Jumping nimbly about, this small-bodied Pokémon takes advantage of even the slightest opportunity to disorient larger opponents.

items.name: Corvisquire
items.description: The Raven Pokémon. Smart enough to use tools in battle, these Pokémon have been seen picking up rocks and flinging them or using ropes to wrap up enemies.

items.name: Corviknight
items.description: The Raven Pokémon. With their great intellect and flying skills, the black luster of its steel body could drive terror into the heart of any foe.

items.name: Blipbug
items.description: The Larva Pokémon. Often found in gardens, this Pokémon has hairs on its body that it uses to assess its surroundings.

items.name: Dottler
items.description: The Radome Pokémon. It barely moves, but it's still alive. Hiding in its shell without food or water seems to have awakened its psychic powers.

items.name: Orbeetle
items.description: The Seven Spot Pokémon. It's famous for its high level of intelligence, and the large size of its brain is proof that it also possesses immense psychic power.

items.name: Nickit
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. Cunning and cautious, this Pokémon survives by stealing food from others. It erases its tracks with swipes of its tail as it makes off with its plunder.

items.name: Thievul
items.description: The Fox Pokémon. It secretly marks potential targets with a scent. By following the scent, it stalks its targets and steals from them when they least expect it.

items.name: Gossifleur
items.description: The Flowering Pokémon. It anchors itself in the ground with its single leg, then basks in the sun. After absorbing enough sunlight, its petals spread as it blooms brilliantly.
items.specialAbilityText: This Pokémon always has the Drifter ability, along with one other.

items.name: Eldegoss
items.description: The Cotton Bloom Pokémon. The seeds attached to its cotton fluff are full of nutrients. It spreads them on the wind so that plants and other Pokémon can benefit from them.
items.specialAbilityText: This Pokémon always has the Drifter ability, along with one other.

items.name: Wooloo
items.description: The Sheep Pokémon. Its curly fleece is such an effective cushion that this Pokémon could fall off a cliff and stand right back up at the bottom, unharmed.

items.name: Dubwool
items.description: The Sheep Pokémon. Weave a carpet from its springy wool, and you end up with something closer to a trampoline. You'll start to bounce the moment you set foot on it.

items.name: Chewtle
items.description: The Snapping Pokémon. It starts off battles by attacking with its rock-hard horn, but as soon as the opponent flinches, this Pokémon bites down and never lets go.

items.name: Drednaw
items.description: The Bite Pokémon. With jaws that can shear through steel rods, this highly aggressive Pokémon chomps down on its unfortunate prey.

items.name: Yamper
items.description: The Puppy Pokémon. This gluttonous Pokémon only assists people with their work because it wants treats. As it runs, it crackles with electricity.

items.name: Boltund
items.description: The Dog Pokémon. This Pokémon generates electricity and channels it into its legs to keep them going strong. Boltund can run nonstop for three full days.

items.name: Rolycoly
items.description: The Coal Pokémon. Most of its body has the same composition as coal. Fittingly, this Pokémon was first discovered in coal mines about 400 years ago.

items.name: Carkol
items.description: The Coal Pokémon. By rapidly rolling its legs, it can travel at over 18 mph. The temperature of the flames it breathes exceeds 1,800 degrees Fahrenheit.

items.name: Coalossal
items.description: The Coal Pokémon. While it's engaged in battle, its mountain of coal will burn bright red, sending off sparks that scorch the surrounding area.

items.name: Applin

conditions.value: inhabiting a green or gold apple

items.description: The Apple Core Pokémon. It spends its entire life inside an apple. It hides from its natural enemies, bird Pokémon, by pretending it's just an apple and nothing more.

items.name: Flapple
items.description: The Apple Wing Pokémon. It flies on wings of apple skin and spits a powerful acid. It can also change its shape into that of an apple.

items.name: Appletun
items.description: The Apple Nectar Pokémon. Its body is covered in sweet nectar, and the skin on its back is especially yummy. A nectarous scent wafts from its body, luring in the bug Pokémon it preys on.

items.name: Silicobra
items.description: The Sand Snake Pokémon. As it digs, it swallows sand and stores it in its neck pouch. The pouch can hold more than 17 pounds of sand.

items.name: Sandaconda
items.description: The Sand Snake Pokémon. When it contracts its body, over 220 pounds of sand sprays from its nose. If it ever runs out of sand, it becomes disheartened.

items.name: Cramorant
items.description: The Gulp Pokémon. This hungry Pokémon swallows Arrokuda whole. Occasionally, it makes a mistake and tries to swallow a Pokémon other than its preferred prey.

items.name: Arrokuda
items.description: The Rush Pokémon. If it sees any movement around it, this Pokémon charges for it straightaway, leading with its sharply pointed jaw. It's very proud of that jaw.

items.name: Barraskewda
items.description: The Skewer Pokémon. It spins its tail fins to propel itself, surging forward at speeds of over 100 knots before ramming prey and spearing into them.

items.name: Toxel

conditions.value: its nature is Hardy, Brave, Adamant, Naughty, Docile, Impish, Lax, Hasty, Jolly, Naive, Rash, Sassy, or Quirky
its nature is NOT Hardy, Brave, Adamant, Naughty, Docile, Impish, Lax, Hasty, Jolly, Naive, Rash, Sassy, or Quirky

items.description: The Baby Pokémon. It stores poison in an internal poison sac and secretes that poison through its skin. If you touch this Pokémon, a tingling sensation follows.

items.name: Toxtricity (Amped)
items.description: The Punk Pokémon. This short-tempered and aggressive Pokémon chugs stagnant water to absorb any toxins it might contain.

items.name: Toxtricity (Low Key)
items.description: The Punk Pokémon. Capable of generating 15,000 volts of electricity, this Pokémon looks down on all that would challenge it.

items.name: Sizzlipede
items.description: The Radiator Pokémon. It wraps prey up with its heated body, cooking them in its coils. Once they're well-done, it will voraciously nibble them down to the last morsel.

items.name: Centiskorch
items.description: The Radiator Pokémon. When it heats up, its body temperature reaches about 1,500 degrees Fahrenheit. It lashes its body like a whip and launches itself at enemies.

items.name: Clobbopus
items.description: The Tantrum Pokémon. It's very curious, but its means of investigating things is to try to punch them with its tentacles. The search for food is what brings it onto land.

items.name: Grapploct
items.description: The Tantrum Pokémon. A body made up of nothing but muscle makes the grappling moves this Pokémon performs with its tentacles tremendously powerful.

items.name: Sinistea
items.description: The Black Tea Pokémon. This Pokémon is said to have been born when a lonely spirit possessed a cold, leftover cup of tea.

items.name: Polteageist
items.description: The Black Tea Pokémon. This species lives in antique teapots. Most pots are forgeries, but on rare occasions, an authentic work is found.

items.name: Hatenna
items.description: The Calm Pokémon. Via the protrusion on its head, it senses other creatures’ emotions. If you don’t have a calm disposition, it will never warm up to you.

items.name: Hattrem
items.description: The Serene Pokémon. No matter who you are, if you bring strong emotions near this Pokémon, it will silence you violently.

items.name: Hatterene
items.description: The Silent Pokémon. It emits psychic power strong enough to cause headaches as a deterrent to the approach of others.

items.name: Impidimp
items.description: The Wily Pokémon. Through its nose, it sucks in the emanations produced by people and Pokémon when they feel annoyed. It thrives off this negative energy.

items.name: Morgrem
items.description: The Devious Pokémon. When it gets down on all fours as if to beg for forgiveness, it’s trying to lure opponents in so that it can stab them with its spear-like hair.

items.name: Grimmsnarl
items.description: The Bulk Up Pokémon. With the hair wrapped around its body helping to enhance its muscles, this Pokémon can overwhelm even Machamp.

items.name: Obstagoon
items.description: The Blocking Pokémon. It evolved after experiencing numerous fights. While crossing its arms, it lets out a shout that would make any opponent flinch.

items.name: Perrserker
items.description: The Scratch Cat Pokémon. What appears to be an iron helmet is actually hardened hair. This Pokémon lives for the thrill of battle.

items.name: Cursola
items.description: The Coral Pokémon. Its shell is overflowing with its heightened otherworldly energy. The ectoplasm serves as protection for this Pokémon's core spirit.

items.name: Sirfetch'd
items.description: The Wild Duck Pokémon. Only Farfetch'd that have survived many battles can attain this evolution. When this Pokémon's leek withers, it will retire from combat.

items.name: Mr. Rime
items.description: The Dancing Pokémon. It's highly skilled at tap-dancing. It waves its cane of ice in time with its graceful movements.

items.name: Runerigus
items.description: The Grudge Pokémon. Never touch its shadowlike body, or you'll be shown the horrific memories behind the picture carved into it.

items.name: Milcery
items.description: The Cream Pokémon. They say that any patisserie visited by Milcery is guaranteed success and good fortune.

items.name: Alcremie
items.description: The Cream Pokémon. Alcremie can produce whipped cream, which becomes richer the happier Alcremie is feeling. Desserts made using this cream are invariably delicious, so many pastry chefs strive to have an Alcremie as their partner.

items.name: Falinks
items.description: The Formation Pokémon. The leader, known as the brass, uses its extendible horn to issue orders to the others when it’s time to change formation.

items.name: Pincurchin
items.description: The Sea Urchin Pokémon. This Pokémon is so timid that even brushing against seaweed will make it discharge electricity in surprise. Its lips do not conduct electricity.

items.name: Snom
items.description: The Worm Pokemon. Within its internal organs, Snom amplifies the frigid air it gets from eating snow and then uses this amplified air to create icicle-like spikes.

items.name: Frosmoth
items.description: The Frost Moth Pokémon. Icy scales fall from its wings like snow as it flies over fields and mountains. The temperature of its wings is less than -290 degrees Fahrenheit.

items.name: Stonjourner
items.description: The Big Rock Pokémon. It stands in grasslands, watching the sun’s descent from zenith to horizon. This Pokémon has a talent for delivering dynamic kicks.

items.name: Eiscue
items.description: The Penguin Pokémon. It drifted in on the flow of ocean waters from a frigid place. It keeps its head iced constantly to make sure it stays nice and cold.

items.name: Indeedee ♂
items.description: The Emotion Pokémon. It uses the horns on its head to sense the emotions of others. Males will act as valets for those they serve, looking after their every need.

items.name: Indeedee ♀
items.description: The Emotion Pokémon. They diligently serve people and Pokémon so they can gather feelings of gratitude. The females are particularly good at babysitting.

items.name: Morpeko
items.description: The Two-Sided Pokémon. As it eats the seeds stored up in its pocket-like pouches, this Pokémon is not just satisfying its constant hunger. It’s also generating electricity.

items.name: Cufant
items.description: The Copperderm Pokémon. It digs up the ground with its trunk. It’s also very strong, being able to carry loads of over five tons without any problem at all.

items.name: Copperajah
items.description: The Copperderm Pokémon. They came over from another region long ago and worked together with humans. Their green skin is resistant to water.

items.name: Dracozolt
items.description: The Fossil Pokémon. In ancient times, it was unbeatable thanks to its powerful lower body, but it went extinct anyway after it depleted all its plant-based food sources.

items.name: Arctozolt
items.description: The Fossil Pokémon. The shaking of its freezing upper half is what generates its electricity. It has a hard time walking around.

items.name: Dracovish
items.description: The Fossil Pokémon. Powerful legs and jaws made it the apex predator of its time. Its own overhunting of its prey was what drove it to extinction.

items.name: Arctovish
items.description: The Fossil Pokémon. Though it’s able to capture prey by freezing its surroundings, it has trouble eating the prey afterward because its mouth is on top of its head.

items.name: Duraludon
items.description: The Alloy Pokémon. Its body resembles polished metal, and it’s both lightweight and strong. The only drawback is that it rusts easily.

items.name: Dreepy
items.description: The Lingering Pokémon. After being reborn as a ghost Pokémon, Dreepy wanders the areas it used to inhabit back when it was alive in prehistoric seas.

items.name: Drakloak
items.description: The Caretaker Pokémon. It’s capable of flying faster than 120 mph. It battles alongside Dreepy and dotes on them until they successfully evolve.

items.name: Dragapult
items.description: The Stealth Pokémon. When it isn’t battling, it keeps Dreepy in the holes on its horns. Once a fight starts, it launches the Dreepy like supersonic missiles.

items.name: Zacian
items.description: The Warrior Pokémon. Known as a legendary hero, this Pokémon absorbs metal particles, transforming them into a weapon it uses to battle.

items.name: Zacian (Crowned)
items.description: The Warrior Pokémon. Known as a legendary hero, this Pokémon absorbs metal particles, transforming them into a weapon it uses to battle.

items.name: Zamazenta
items.description: The Warrior Pokémon. In times past, it worked together with a king of the people to save the Galar region. It absorbs metal that it then uses in battle.

items.name: Zamazenta (Crowned)
items.description: The Warrior Pokémon. In times past, it worked together with a king of the people to save the Galar region. It absorbs metal that it then uses in battle.

items.name: Eternatus
items.description: The Gigantic Pokémon. The core on its chest absorbs energy emanating from the lands of the Galar region. This energy is what allows Eternatus to stay active.

items.name: Eternatus (Eternamax)
items.description: The Gigantic Pokémon. The core on its chest absorbs energy emanating from the lands of the Galar region. This energy is what allows Eternatus to stay active.

items.name: Kubfu
items.description: The Wushu Pokémon. Kubfu trains hard to perfect its moves. The moves it masters will determine which form it takes when it evolves.

items.name: Urshifu (Single Strike)
items.description: The Wushu Pokémon. This form of Urshifu is a strong believer in the one-hit KO. Its strategy is to leap in close to foes and land a devastating blow with a hardened fist.

items.name: Urshifu (Rapid Strike)
items.description: The Wushu Pokémon. This form of Urshifu is a strong believer in defeating foes by raining many blows down on them. Its strikes are nonstop, flowing like a river.

items.name: Zarude
items.description: The Rogue Monkey Pokémon. Within dense forests, this Pokémon lives in a pack with others of its kind. It’s incredibly aggressive, and the other Pokémon of the forest fear it.

items.name: Regieleki
items.description: The Electron Pokémon. This Pokémon is a cluster of electrical energy. It’s said that removing the rings on Regieleki’s body will unleash the Pokémon’s latent power.

items.name: Regidrago
items.description: The Dragon Orb Pokémon. An academic theory proposes that Regidrago’s arms were once the head of an ancient dragon Pokémon. The theory remains unproven.

items.name: Glastrier
items.description: The Wild Horse Pokémon. Glastrier emits intense cold from its hooves. It’s also a belligerent Pokémon—anything it wants, it takes by force.

items.name: Spectrier
items.description: The Swift Horse Pokémon. It probes its surroundings with all its senses save one—it doesn’t use its sense of sight. Spectrier’s kicks are said to separate soul from body.

items.name: Calyrex
items.description: The King Pokémon. Calyrex is a merciful Pokémon, capable of providing healing and blessings. It reigned over the Galar region in times of yore.

items.name: Calyrex (Ice Rider)
items.description: The High King Pokémon. According to lore, this Pokémon showed no mercy to those who got in its way, yet it would heal its opponents’ wounds after battle.

items.name: Calyrex (Shadow Rider)
items.description: The High King Pokémon. Legend says that by using its power to see all events from past to future, this Pokémon saved the creatures of a forest from a meteorite strike.

items.name: Hisuian Growlithe
items.description: The Scout Pokémon. They patrol their territory in pairs. I believe the igneous rock components in the fur of this species are the result of volcanic activity in its habitat.

items.name: Hisuian Arcanine
items.description: The Legendary Pokémon. Snaps at its foes with fangs cloaked in blazing flame. Despite its bulk, it deftly feints every which way, leading opponents on a deceptively merry chase as it all but dances around them.

items.name: Hisuian Voltorb
items.description: The Sphere Pokémon. An enigmatic Pokémon that happens to bear a resemblance to a Poké Ball. When excited, it discharges the electric current it has stored in its belly, then lets out a great, uproarious laugh.

items.name: Hisuian Electrode
items.description: The Sphere Pokémon. The tissue on the surface of its body is curiously similar in composition to an Apricorn. When irritated, this Pokémon lets loose an electric current equal to 20 lightning bolts.

items.name: Hisuian Typhlosion
items.description: The Ghost Flame Pokémon. Said to purify lost, forsaken souls with its flames and guide them to the afterlife. I believe its form has been influenced by the energy of the sacred mountain towering at Hisui’s center.

items.name: Hisuian Qwilfish
items.description: The Balloon Pokémon. Fishers detest this troublesome Pokémon because it sprays poison from its spines, getting it everywhere. A different form of Qwilfish lives in other regions.

items.name: Hisuian Sneasel
items.description: The Sharp Claw Pokémon. Its sturdy, curved claws are ideal for traversing precipitous cliffs. From the tips of these claws drips a venom that infiltrates the nerves of any prey caught in Sneasel’s grasp.

items.name: Hisuian Samurott
items.description: The Formidable Pokémon. Hard of heart and deft of blade, this rare form of Samurott is a product of the Pokémon’s evolution in the region of Hisui. Its turbulent blows crash into foes like ceaseless pounding waves.

items.name: Hisuian Lilligant
items.description: The Spinning Pokémon. I suspect that its well-developed legs are the result of a life spent on mountains covered in deep snow. The scent it exudes from its flower crown heartens those in proximity.

items.name: Hisuian Zorua
items.description: The Spiteful Fox Pokémon. A once-departed soul, returned to life in Hisui. Derives power from resentment, which rises as energy atop its head and takes on the forms of foes. In this way, Zorua vents lingering malice.

items.name: Hisuian Zoroark
items.description: The Baneful Fox Pokémon. With its disheveled white fur, it looks like an embodiment of death. Heedless of its own safety, Zoroark attacks its nemeses with a bitter energy so intense, it lacerates Zoroark’s own body.

items.name: Hisuian Braviary
items.description: The Battle Cry Pokémon. Screaming a bloodcurdling battle cry, this huge and ferocious bird Pokémon goes out on the hunt. It blasts lakes with shock waves, then scoops up any prey that float to the water’s surface.

items.name: Hisuian Sliggoo
items.description: The Snail Pokémon. A creature given to melancholy. I suspect its metallic shell developed as a result of the mucus on its skin reacting with the iron in Hisui’s water.

items.name: Hisuian Goodra
items.description: The Shell Bunker Pokémon. Able to freely control the hardness of its metallic shell. It loathes solitude and is extremely clingy—it will fume and run riot if those dearest to it ever leave its side.

items.name: Hisuian Avalugg
items.description: The Iceberg Pokémon. The armor of ice covering its lower jaw puts steel to shame and can shatter rocks with ease. This Pokémon barrels along steep mountain paths, cleaving through the deep snow.

items.name: Hisuian Decidueye
items.description: The Arrow Quill Pokémon. The air stored inside the rachises of Decidueye’s feathers insulates the Pokémon against Hisui’s extreme cold. This is firm proof that evolution can be influenced by environment.

items.name: Wyrdeer
items.description: The Big Horn Pokémon. The black orbs shine with an uncanny light when the Pokémon is erecting invisible barriers. The fur shed from its beard retains heat well and is a highly useful material for winter clothing.

items.name: Kleavor
items.description: The Axe Pokémon. A violent creature that fells towering trees with its crude axes and shields itself with hard stone. If one should chance upon this Pokémon in the wilds, one's only recourse is to flee.

items.name: Ursaluna
items.description: The Peat Pokémon. I believe it was Hisui's swampy terrain that gave Ursaluna its burly physique and newfound capacity to manipulate peat at will.

items.name: Bloodmoon Ursaluna
items.description: The Peat Pokémon. This special Ursaluna can see in the dark with its left eye and protects itself with mud that is as hard as iron.

items.name: Basculegion ♂
items.description: The Big Fish Pokémon. Clads itself in the souls of comrades that perished before fulfilling their goals of journeying upstream. No other species throughout all Hisui's rivers is Basculegion's equal.

items.name: Basculegion ♀
items.description: The Big Fish Pokémon. Clads itself in the souls of comrades that perished before fulfilling their goals of journeying upstream. No other species throughout all Hisui's rivers is Basculegion's equal.

items.name: Sneasler
items.description: The Free Climb Pokémon. Because of Sneasler's virulent poison and daunting physical prowess, no other species could hope to best it on the frozen highlands. Preferring solitude, this species does not form packs.

items.name: Overqwil
items.description: The Pin Cluster Pokémon. Its lancelike spikes and savage temperament have earned it the nickname ”sea fiend.” It slurps up poison to nourish itself.

items.name: Enamorus
items.description: The Love-Hate Pokémon. When it flies to this land from across the sea, the bitter winter comes to an end. According to legend, this Pokémon's love gives rise to the budding of fresh life across Hisui.

items.name: Paldean Tauros (Combat Breed)
items.description: The Wild Bull Pokémon. This Pokémon has a muscular body and excels at close-quarters combat. It uses its short horns to strike the opponent’s weak spots.

items.name: Paldean Tauros (Blaze Breed)
items.description: The Wild Bull Pokémon. When heated by fire energy, its horns can get hotter than 1,800 degrees Fahrenheit. Those gored by them will suffer both wounds and burns.

items.name: Paldean Tauros (Aqua Breed)
items.description: The Wild Bull Pokémon. This Pokémon blasts water from holes on the tips of its horns—the high-pressure jets pierce right through Tauros’s enemies.

items.name: Paldean Wooper
items.description: The Poison Fish Pokémon. After losing a territorial struggle, Wooper began living on land. The Pokémon changed over time, developing a poisonous film to protect its body.

items.name: Sprigatito
items.description: The Grass Cat Pokemon. The sweet scent its body gives off mesmerizes those around it. The scent grows stronger when this Pokémon is in the sun.

items.name: Floragato
items.description: The Grass Cat Pokémon. The hardness of Floragato’s fur depends on the Pokémon’s mood. When Floragato is prepared to battle, its fur becomes pointed and needle sharp.

items.name: Meowscarada
items.description: The Magician Pokémon. With skillful misdirection, it rigs foes with pollen-packed flower bombs. Meowscarada sets off the bombs before its foes realize what’s going on.

items.name: Fuecoco
items.description: The Fire Croc Pokémon. It lies on warm rocks and uses the heat absorbed by its square-shaped scales to create fire energy.

items.name: Crocalor
items.description: The Fire Croc Pokémon. The combination of Crocalor’s fire energy and overflowing vitality has caused an egg-shaped fireball to appear on the Pokémon’s head.

items.name: Skeledirge
items.description: The Singer Pokémon. The fiery bird changes shape when Skeledirge sings. Rumor has it that the bird was born when the fireball on Skeledirge’s head gained a soul.

items.name: Quaxly
items.description: The Duckling Pokémon. This Pokémon migrated to Paldea from distant lands long ago. The gel secreted by its feathers repels water and grime.

items.name: Quaxwell
items.description: The Practicing Pokémon. These Pokémon constantly run through shallow waters to train their legs, then compete with each other to see which of them kicks most gracefully.

items.name: Quaquaval
items.description: The Dancer Pokémon. A single kick from a Quaquaval can send a truck rolling. This Pokémon uses its powerful legs to perform striking dances from far-off lands.

items.name: Lechonk
items.description: The Hog Pokémon. It searches for food all day. It possesses a keen sense of smell but doesn’t use it for anything other than foraging.

items.name: Oinkologne ♂
items.description: The Hog Pokémon. Oinkologne is proud of its fine, glossy skin. It emits a concentrated scent from the tip of its tail.

items.name: Oinkologne ♀
items.description: The Hog Pokémon. This is a meticulous Pokémon that likes to keep things tidy. It shrouds itself in a floral aroma that soothes the Pokémon around it.

items.name: Tarountula
items.description: The String Ball Pokémon. The ball of threads wrapped around its body is elastic enough to deflect the scythes of Scyther, this Pokémon’s natural enemy.

items.name: Spidops
items.description: The Trap Pokémon. It clings to branches and ceilings using its threads and moves without a sound. It takes out its prey before the prey even notices it.

items.name: Nymble
items.description: The Grasshopper Pokémon. It has its third set of legs folded up. When it’s in a tough spot, this Pokémon jumps over 30 feet using the strength of its legs.

items.name: Lokix
items.description: The Grasshopper Pokémon. When it decides to fight all out, it stands on its previously folded legs to enter Showdown Mode. It neutralizes its enemies in short order.

items.name: Pawmi
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. It has underdeveloped electric sacs on its cheeks. These sacs can produce electricity only if Pawmi rubs them furiously with the pads on its forepaws.

items.name: Pawmo
items.description: The Mouse Pokémon. When its group is attacked, Pawmo is the first to leap into battle, defeating enemies with a fighting technique that utilizes electric shocks.

items.name: Pawmot
items.description: The Hands-On Pokémon. This Pokémon normally is slow to react, but once it enters battle, it will strike down its enemies with lightning-fast movements.

items.name: Tandemaus
items.description: The Couple Pokémon. Exhibiting great teamwork, they use their incisors to cut pieces out of any material that might be useful for a nest, then make off with them.

items.name: Maushold
items.description: The Family Pokémon. The two little ones just appeared one day. The group might be a family of related Pokémon, but nobody knows for sure.

items.name: Fidough
items.description: The Puppy Pokémon. This Pokémon is smooth and moist to the touch. Yeast in Fidough’s breath induces fermentation in the Pokémon’s vicinity.

items.name: Dachsbun
items.description: The Dog Pokémon. The pleasant aroma that emanates from this Pokémon’s body helps wheat grow, so Dachsbun has been treasured by farming villages.

items.name: Smoliv
items.description: The Olive Pokémon. It protects itself from enemies by emitting oil from the fruit on its head. This oil is bitter and astringent enough to make someone flinch.

items.name: Dolliv
items.description: The Olive Pokémon. Dolliv shares its tasty, fresh-scented oil with others. This species has coexisted with humans since times long gone.

items.name: Arboliva
items.description: The Olive Pokémon. This calm Pokémon is very compassionate. It will share its delicious, nutrient-rich oil with weakened Pokémon.

items.name: Squawkabilly
items.description: The Parrot Pokémon. These Pokémon prefer to live in cities. They form flocks based on the color of their feathers, and they fight over territory.

items.name: Nacli
items.description: The Rock Salt Pokémon. It was born in a layer of rock salt deep under the earth. This species was particularly treasured in the old days, as they would share precious salt.

items.name: Naclstack
items.description: The Rock Salt Pokémon. This Pokémon dry cures its prey by spraying salt over them. The curing process steals away the water in the prey’s body.

items.name: Garganacl
items.description: The Rock Salt Pokémon. Garganacl will rub its fingertips together and sprinkle injured Pokémon with salt. Even severe wounds will promptly heal afterward.

items.name: Charcadet
items.description: The Fire Child Pokémon. Burnt charcoal came to life and became a Pokémon. Possessing a fiery fighting spirit, Charcadet will battle even tough opponents.

items.name: Armarouge
items.description: The Fire Warrior Pokémon. Armarouge evolved through the use of a set of armor that belonged to a distinguished warrior. This Pokémon is incredibly loyal.

items.name: Ceruledge
items.description: The Fire Blades Pokémon. The fiery blades on its arms burn fiercely with the lingering resentment of a sword wielder who fell before accomplishing their goal.

items.name: Tadbulb
items.description: The EleTadpole Pokémon. Tadbulb shakes its tail to generate electricity. If it senses danger, it will make its head blink on and off to alert its allies.

items.name: Bellibolt
items.description: The EleFrog Pokémon. When this Pokémon expands and contracts its wobbly body, the belly-button dynamo in its stomach produces a huge amount of electricity.

items.name: Wattrel
items.description: The Storm Petrel Pokémon. When its wings catch the wind, the bones within produce electricity. This Pokémon dives into the ocean, catching prey by electrocuting them.

items.name: Kilowattrel
items.description: The Frigatebird Pokémon. Kilowattrel inflates its throat sac to amplify its electricity. By riding the wind, this Pokémon can fly over 430 miles in a day.

items.name: Maschiff
items.description: The Rascal Pokémon. It always scowls in an attempt to make opponents take it seriously, but even crying children will burst into laughter when they see Maschiff’s face.

items.name: Mabosstiff
items.description: The Boss Pokémon. This Pokémon can store energy in its large dewlap. Mabosstiff unleashes this energy all at once to blow away enemies.

items.name: Shroodle
items.description: The Toxic Mouse Pokémon. Though usually a mellow Pokémon, it will sink its sharp, poison-soaked front teeth into any that anger it, causing paralysis in the object of its ire.

items.name: Grafaiai
items.description: The Toxic Monkey Pokémon. The color of the poisonous saliva depends on what the Pokémon eats. Grafaiai covers its fingers in its saliva and draws patterns on trees in forests.

items.name: Bramblin
items.description: The Tumbleweed Pokémon. A soul unable to move on to the afterlife was blown around by the wind until it got tangled up with dried grass and became a Pokémon.

items.name: Brambleghast
items.description: The Tumbleweed Pokémon. It will open the branches of its head to envelop its prey. Once it absorbs all the life energy it needs, it expels the prey and discards it.

items.name: Toedscool
items.description: The Woodear Pokémon. Toedscool lives in muggy forests. The flaps that fall from its body are chewy and very delicious.

items.name: Toedscruel
items.description: The Woodear Pokémon. These Pokémon gather into groups and form colonies deep within forests. They absolutely hate it when strangers approach.

items.name: Klawf
items.description: The Ambush Pokémon. Klawf hangs upside-down from cliffs, waiting for prey. But Klawf can’t remain in this position for long because its blood rushes to its head.

items.name: Capsakid
items.description: The Spicy Pepper Pokémon. The more sunlight this Pokémon bathes in, the more spicy chemicals are produced by its body, and thus the spicier its moves become.

items.name: Scovillain
items.description: The Spicy Pepper Pokémon. The red head converts spicy chemicals into fire energy and blasts the surrounding area with a super spicy stream of flame.

items.name: Rellor
items.description: The Rolling Pokémon. This Pokémon creates a mud ball by mixing sand and dirt with psychic energy. It treasures its mud ball more than its own life.

items.name: Rabsca
items.description: The Rolling Pokémon. The body that supports the ball barely moves. Therefore, it is thought that the true body of this Pokémon is actually inside the ball.

items.name: Flittle
items.description: The Frill Pokémon. Flittle’s toes levitate about half an inch above the ground because of the psychic power emitted from the frills on the Pokémon’s belly.

items.name: Espathra
items.description: The Ostrich Pokémon. It immobilizes opponents by bathing them in psychic power from its large eyes. Despite its appearance, it has a vicious temperament.

items.name: Tinkatink
items.description: The Metalsmith Pokémon. It swings its handmade hammer around to protect itself, but the hammer is often stolen by Pokémon that eat metal.

items.name: Tinkatuff
items.description: The Hammer Pokémon. This Pokémon will attack groups of Pawniard and Bisharp, gathering metal from them in order to create a large and sturdy hammer.

items.name: Tinkaton
items.description: The Hammer Pokémon. This intelligent Pokémon has a very daring disposition. It knocks rocks into the sky with its hammer, aiming for flying Corviknight.

items.name: Wiglett
items.description: The Garden Eel Pokémon. This Pokémon can pick up the scent of a Veluza just over 65 feet away and will hide itself in the sand.

items.name: Wugtrio
items.description: The Garden Eel Pokémon. It has a vicious temperament, contrary to what its appearance may suggest. It wraps its long bodies around prey, then drags the prey into its den.

items.name: Bombirdier
items.description: The Item Drop Pokémon. It gathers things up in an apron made from shed feathers added to the Pokémon’s chest feathers, then drops those things from high places for fun.

items.name: Finizen
items.description: The Dolphin Pokémon. It likes playing with others of its kind using the water ring on its tail. It uses ultrasonic waves to sense the emotions of other living creatures.

items.name: Palafin
items.description: The Dolphin Pokémon. This Pokémon changes its appearance if it hears its allies calling for help. Palafin will never show anybody its moment of transformation.

items.name: Varoom
items.description: The Single-Cyl Pokémon. It is said that this Pokémon was born when an unknown poison Pokémon entered and inspirited an engine left at a scrap-processing factory.

items.name: Revavroom
items.description: The Multi-Cyl Pokémon. It creates a gas out of poison and minerals from rocks. It then detonates the gas in its cylinders—now numbering eight—to generate energy.

items.name: Cyclizar
items.description: The Mount Pokémon. Apparently Cyclizar has been allowing people to ride on its back since ancient times. Depictions of this have been found in 10,000-year-old murals.

items.name: Orthworm
items.description: The Earthworm Pokémon. When attacked, this Pokémon will wield the tendrils on its body like fists and pelt the opponent with a storm of punches.

items.name: Glimmet
items.description: The Ore Pokémon. It absorbs nutrients from cave walls. The petals it wears are made of crystallized poison.

items.name: Glimmora
items.description: The Ore Pokémon. When this Pokémon detects danger, it will open up its crystalline petals and fire beams from its conical body.

items.name: Greavard
items.description: The Ghost Dog Pokémon. It is said that a dog Pokémon that died in the wild without ever interacting with a human was reborn as this Pokémon.

items.name: Houndstone
items.description: The Ghost Dog Pokémon. Houndstone spends most of its time sleeping in graveyards. Among all the dog Pokémon, this one is most loyal to its master.

items.name: Flamigo
items.description: The Synchronize Pokémon. This Pokémon apparently ties the base of its neck into a knot so that energy stored in its belly does not escape from its beak.

items.name: Cetoddle
items.description: The Terra Whale Pokémon. This species left the ocean and began living on land a very long time ago. It seems to be closely related to Wailmer.

items.name: Cetitan
items.description: The Terra Whale Pokémon. This Pokémon wanders around snowy, icy areas. It protects its body with powerful muscles and a thick layer of fat under its skin.

items.name: Veluza
items.description: The Jettison Pokémon. When Veluza discards unnecessary flesh, its mind becomes honed and its psychic power increases. The spare flesh has a mild but delicious flavor.

items.name: Dondozo
items.description: The Big Catfish Pokémon. This Pokémon is a glutton, but it’s bad at getting food. It teams up with a Tatsugiri to catch prey.

items.name: Tatsugiri
items.description: The Mimicry Pokémon. This is a small dragon Pokémon. It lives inside the mouth of Dondozo to protect itself from enemies on the outside.

items.name: Annihilape
items.description: The Rage Monkey Pokémon. When its anger rose beyond a critical point, this Pokémon gained power that is unfettered by the limits of its physical body.

items.name: Clodsire
items.description: The Spiny Fish Pokémon. When attacked, this Pokémon will retaliate by sticking thick spines out from its body. It’s a risky move that puts everything on the line.

items.name: Farigiraf
items.description: The Long Neck Pokémon. Now that the brain waves from the head and tail are synced up, the psychic power of this Pokémon is 10 times stronger than Girafarig’s.

items.name: Dudunsparce
items.description: The Land Snake Pokémon. This Pokémon uses its hard tail to make its nest by boring holes into bedrock deep underground. The nest can reach lengths of over six miles.

items.name: Kingambit
items.description: The Big Blade Pokémon. Only a Bisharp that stands above all others in its vast army can evolve into Kingambit.

items.name: Great Tusk
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This creature resembles a mysterious Pokémon that, according to a paranormal magazine, has lived since ancient times.

items.name: Scream Tail
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It resembles a mysterious Pokémon described in a paranormal magazine as a Jigglypuff from one billion years ago.

items.name: Brute Bonnet
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It bears a slight resemblance to a Pokémon described in a dubious magazine as a cross between a dinosaur and a mushroom.

items.name: Flutter Mane
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It has similar features to a ghostly pterosaur that was covered in a paranormal magazine, but the two have little else in common.

items.name: Slither Wing
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This Pokémon somewhat resembles an ancient form of Volcarona that was introduced in a dubious magazine.

items.name: Sandy Shocks
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It slightly resembles a Magneton that lived for 10,000 years and was featured in an article in a paranormal magazine.

items.name: Iron Treads
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This Pokémon closely resembles a scientific weapon that a paranormal magazine claimed was sent to this planet by aliens.

items.name: Iron Bundle
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. Its shape is similar to a robot featured in a paranormal magazine article. The robot was said to have been created by an ancient civilization.

items.name: Iron Hands
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It is very similar to a cyborg covered exclusively by a paranormal magazine. The cyborg was said to be the modified form of a certain athlete.

items.name: Iron Jugulis
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It resembles a certain Pokémon introduced in a paranormal magazine, described as the offspring of a Hydreigon that fell in love with a robot.

items.name: Iron Moth
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This Pokémon resembles an unknown object described in a paranormal magazine as a UFO sent to observe humanity.

items.name: Iron Thorns
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It has some similarities to a Pokémon introduced in a dubious magazine as a Tyranitar from one billion years into the future.

items.name: Frigibax
items.description: The Ice Fin Pokémon. Frigibax absorbs heat through its dorsal fin and converts the heat into ice energy. The higher the temperature, the more energy Frigibax stores.

items.name: Arctibax
items.description: The Ice Fin Pokémon. Arctibax freezes the air around it, protecting its face with an ice mask and turning its dorsal fin into a blade of ice.

items.name: Baxcalibur
items.description: The Ice Dragon Pokémon. This Pokémon blasts cryogenic air out from its mouth. This air can instantly freeze even liquid-hot lava.

items.name: Gimmighoul (Chest)

conditions.value: when this Pokémon has collected 999 gimmighoul coins (chest form starts with 50+1d100, roaming form starts with 1d20)

items.description: The Coin Chest Pokémon. This Pokémon was born inside a treasure chest about 1,500 years ago. It sucks the life-force out of scoundrels who try to steal the treasure.

items.name: Gimmighoul (Roaming)

conditions.value: when this Pokémon has collected 999 gimmighoul coins (chest form starts with 50+1d100, roaming form starts with 1d20)

items.description: The Coin Hunter Pokémon. This Pokémon was born from passion that seeped into a coin. It wanders, apparently seeking to return to the treasure chest it once inhabited.

items.name: Gholdengo
items.description: The Coin Entity Pokémon. Its body seems to be made up of 1,000 coins. This Pokémon gets along well with others and is quick to make friends with anybody.

items.name: Wo-Chien
items.description: The Ruinous Pokémon. The grudge of a person punished for writing the king’s evil deeds upon wooden tablets has clad itself in dead leaves to become a Pokémon.

items.name: Chien-Pao
items.description: The Ruinous Pokémon. This Pokémon can control 100 tons of fallen snow. It plays around innocently by leaping in and out of avalanches it has caused.

items.name: Ting-Lu
items.description: The Ruinous Pokémon. The fear poured into an ancient ritual vessel has clad itself in rocks and dirt to become a Pokémon.

items.name: Chi-Yu
items.description: The Ruinous Pokémon. It controls flames burning at over 5,400 degrees Fahrenheit. It casually swims through the sea of lava it creates by melting rock and sand.

items.name: Roaring Moon
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. According to an article in a dubious magazine, this Pokémon has some connection to a phenomenon that occurs in a certain region.

items.name: Iron Valiant
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It has some similarities to a mad scientist’s invention covered in a paranormal magazine.

items.name: Koraidon
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This seems to be the Winged King mentioned in an old expedition journal. It was said to have split the land with its bare fists.

items.name: Miraidon
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This seems to be the Iron Serpent mentioned in an old book. The Iron Serpent is said to have turned the land to ash with its lightning.

items.name: Walking Wake
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. This ferocious creature is shrouded in mystery. It's named after an aquatic monster mentioned in an old expedition journal.

items.name: Iron Leaves
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. According to the few eyewitness accounts that exist, it used its shining blades to julienne large trees and boulders.

items.name: Dipplin
items.description: The Candy Apple Pokémon. Dipplin is two creatures in one Pokémon. Its evolution was triggered by a special apple grown only in one place.

items.name: Poltchageist
items.description: The Matcha Pokémon. Supposedly, the regrets of a tea ceremony master who died before perfecting his craft lingered in some matcha and became a Pokémon.

items.name: Sinistcha
items.description: The Matcha Pokémon. It pretends to be tea, trying to fool people into drinking it so it can drain their life-force. Its ruse is generally unsuccessful.

items.name: Okidogi
items.description: The Retainer Pokémon. After all its muscles were stimulated by the toxic chain around its neck, Okidogi transformed and gained a powerful physique.

items.name: Munkidori
items.description: The Retainer Pokémon. The chain is made from toxins that enhance capabilities. It stimulated Munkidori's brain and caused the Pokémon's psychic powers to bloom.

items.name: Fezandipiti
items.description: The Retainer Pokémon. Fezandipiti owes its beautiful looks and lovely voice to the toxic stimulants emanating from the chain wrapped around its body.

items.name: Ogerpon (Teal Mask)
items.description: The Mask Pokémon. This Pokémon's type changes based on which mask it's wearing. It confounds its enemies with nimble movements and kicks.

items.name: Ogerpon (Wellspring Mask)
items.description: The Mask Pokémon. This Pokémon's type changes based on which mask it's wearing. It confounds its enemies with nimble movements and kicks.

items.name: Ogerpon (Heartflame Mask)
items.description: The Mask Pokémon. This Pokémon's type changes based on which mask it's wearing. It confounds its enemies with nimble movements and kicks.

items.name: Ogerpon (Cornerstone Mask)
items.description: The Mask Pokémon. This Pokémon's type changes based on which mask it's wearing. It confounds its enemies with nimble movements and kicks.

items.name: Archaludon
items.description: The Alloy Pokémon. It gathers static electricity from its surroundings. The beams it launches when down on all fours are tremendously powerful.

items.name: Hydrapple
items.description: The Apple Hydra Pokémon. Seven syrpents live inside an apple made of syrup. The syrpent in the center is the commander.

items.name: Gouging Fire
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. There are scant few reports of this creature being sighted. One short video shows it rampaging and spouting pillars of flame.

items.name: Raging Bolt
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It's said to incinerate everything around it with lightning launched from its fur. Very little is known about this creature.

items.name: Iron Boulder
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. It was named after a mysterious object recorded in an old book. Its body seems to be metallic.

items.name: Iron Crown
items.description: The Paradox Pokémon. There was supposedly an incident in which it launched shining blades to cut everything around it to pieces. Little else is known about it.

items.name: Terapagos
items.description: The Tera Pokémon. Terapagos protects itself using its power to transform energy into hard crystals. This Pokémon is the source of the Terastal phenomenon.

items.name: Terapagos (Terastal)
items.description: The Tera Pokémon. Terapagos protects itself using its power to transform energy into hard crystals. This Pokémon is the source of the Terastal phenomenon.

items.name: Terapagos (Stellar)
items.description: The Tera Pokémon. Terapagos protects itself using its power to transform energy into hard crystals. This Pokémon is the source of the Terastal phenomenon.

items.name: Pecharunt
items.description: The Subjugation Pokémon. It feeds others toxic mochi that draw out desires and capabilities. Those who eat the mochi fall under Pecharunt’s control, chained to its will.

items.name: Rookite
items.description: The Blade Shield Pokémon. Rookite protects groups of pawniards from predators both by deflecting attacks with its shield and by crushing its foes with it.

items.name: Belseraph
items.description: The Angel Pokémon. One kind of Ultra Beast. Belseraph's song is thought to gradually "shift" people into the afterlife if they listen for too long.

items.name: Droideon
items.description: The Droid Pokémon. It was born from an experiment to save a dying Eevee. It became dramatically more observant, however, making scientists wonder how much of the original Eevee remains.

items.name: Brawleon
items.description: The Roughhouse Pokémon. Its keen eyes lock onto adversaries with unwavering focus, anticipating their every move in battle.

items.name: Specteon
items.description: The Ethereal Pokémon. Its luminous, sapphire eyes exude an eerie glow, capable of entrancing those who meet its gaze.

items.name: Toxeon
items.description: The Secretion Pokémon. Its fur is constantly drenched with a paralyzing toxin which, despite years of study, has no known medical use.

items.name: Minereon
items.description: The Geodrift Pokémon. The mineral formations on its back and tail can emit an array of dazzling geoglow patterns, which are believed to be a form of communication among its kind.

items.name: Aereon
items.description: The Gliding Pokémon. The currents it creates with its wings carry the soothing scent of fresh air, calming those around it.

items.name: Pesteon
items.description: The Infestant Pokémon. The antennae on its head can detect differences in heat down to a tenth of a degree.

items.name: Terreon
items.description: The Bone Meal Pokémon. The bones it scavenges break down in its fur over time, giving it a distinctive smell and luster.

items.name: Drakeon
items.description: The Elementist Pokémon. Drakeon is the rarest naturally occuring Eevee evolution. Legends speak of its ability to control and manipulate elemental energies, bestowing it with an array of versatile breath attacks.

items.name: Eeveon
items.description: The Domesticated Pokémon. It is born from an absence of evolutionary pressure. Scientists believe increasingly more Eevees will evolve into Eeveon as human influence grows.
